# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: algaculture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:algaculture/2-methylisoborneol] MIB is produced by various blue-green algae (cyanobacteria) and filamentous bacteria in the class Actinomycetia, and also some other prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:algaculture/2-methylisoborneol] The main genera in the cyanobacteria that have been shown to produce MIB include *Oscillatoria*, *Phormidium*, and *Planktothrix*, while the main genus in the Actinomycetia that produces MIB is *Streptomyces*.
[src:algaculture/2-methylisoborneol] They give a musty or earthy odor that can be quite strong if an algal bloom is present.
[src:algaculture/2-methylisoborneol] Subsequent death of the microorganisms will release MIB that is trapped in the cells.
[src:algaculture/2-methylisoborneol] Along with geosmin, the off flavors that result are issues in the seafood industry.
[src:algaculture/2-methylisoborneol] This chemical is the major cause of "muddy" or "dirt" flavors in catfish and crawfish.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Named in honour of Adelaide of Saxe-Meiningen, wife of King William IV, the city was founded in 1836 as the planned capital for a freely settled British colony in Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Colonel William Light, one of Adelaide's founding fathers, designed the city centre and chose its location close to the River Torrens.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Light's design, now listed as national heritage, set out the city centre in a grid layout known as "Light's Vision", interspaced by wide boulevards and large public squares, and entirely surrounded by park lands.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Colonial Adelaide was noted for its leading examples of religious freedom and progressive political reforms and became known as the "City of Churches" due to its diversity of faiths.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] It was Australia's third-most populous city until the postwar era.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Today, Adelaide is one of Australia's most visited travel destinations and hosts many festivals and sporting events, such as the Adelaide 500, Tour Down Under, Gather Round, LIV Golf Adelaide, and the Adelaide Fringe, the world's second largest annual arts festival.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide also hosts men's tennis with an ATP 250 event and women's tennis with a WTA 500 event, and will also become the new host of the Australian MotoGP Grand Prix from 2027.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The city has also been renowned for its automotive industry, having been the original host of the Australian Grand Prix in the FIA Formula One World Championship from 1985 to 1995.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Other features include its food and wine industries, its coastline and hills, its large defence and manufacturing operations, and its emerging space sector, including the Australian Space Agency being headquartered there.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] With one of the world's largest foreign-born populations, Adelaide has consistently ranked within the top-ten most liveable cities globally for much of the 21st century, being named in 2021 the most liveable city in the country and third in the world.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Its aesthetic appeal has also been recognised by *Architectural Digest*, which ranked Adelaide as the most beautiful city in the world in 2024.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] As South Australia's government and commercial centre, Adelaide is the site of many governmental and financial institutions.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Most of these are concentrated in the central business district along the cultural boulevards of North Terrace and King William Street.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has also been classed as a Gamma + level global city as categorised by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network, with the city further linking economic regions to the worldwide economy.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is connected by extensive bus, train and tram networks, all of which are operated by Adelaide Metro, with its main railway terminus at the Adelaide railway station.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The city is also served by Adelaide Airport and Port Adelaide, both of which are among the busiest airports and seaports in Australia, respectively.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The amount of time Aboriginal people have been living in the area around modern-day Adelaide has been described as "millennia", "tens of thousands of years", "thousands of generations", or "innumerable generations".
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] At Hallett Cove Conservation Park in Adelaide's southern suburbs, archaeological evidence of Aboriginal culture has been found dating back 40,000 years.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The area was originally inhabited by the Kaurna people, one of many Aboriginal tribes in South Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The city and parklands area also known as *Tarndanyangga* *Tandanya*, *Tarndanya* or *Tarntanya*.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The name means 'male red kangaroo rock', referring to a rock formation on the site that has now been destroyed.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The surrounding area was an open, grassy plain with patches of trees and shrubs, which had been managed by hundreds of generations.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Kaurna country encompassed the plains stretching north and south of Tarntanya, as well as the wooded foothills of the Mt Lofty Ranges.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The River Torrens was known as the Karrawirra Pari (Red Gum forest river).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] About 300 Kaurna populated the Adelaide area, and were referred to by the settlers as the Cowandilla.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The more than 20 local clans across the plain lived seminomadic lives, with extensive mound settlements where huts were built repeatedly over centuries and a complex social structure, including a class of sorcerers separated from regular society.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Within a few decades of European settlement of South Australia, Kaurna culture was almost completely lost, with the last speaker of Kaurna language having died in 1929.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Extensive documentation by early missionaries and other researchers has enabled a modern revival of both, which has included a commitment by local and state governments to rename or include Kaurna names for many local places.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Based on the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield about colonial reform, Robert Gouger petitioned the British government to create a new colony in Australia, resulting in the passage of the South Australia Act 1834.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Physical establishment of the colony began with the arrival of the first British colonisers in February 1836, followed by the commencement of colonial government in South Australia on 28 December 1836.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Proclaimed by the governor near The Old Gum Tree in what is now the suburb of Glenelg North, this day is annually commemorated in South Australia as Proclamation Day.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Named for Queen Adelaide, the site of the colony's capital was surveyed and laid out by Colonel William Light, the first surveyor-general of South Australia, with his own original, unique and topographically sensitive design.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was established as a planned colony of free settlers, promising civil liberties and freedom from religious persecution, based upon the ideas of Edward Gibbon Wakefield.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Wakefield had read accounts of Australian settlement while in prison in London for attempting to abduct an heiress, and realised that the eastern colonies suffered from a lack of available labour, due to the practice of giving land grants to all arrivals.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Wakefield's idea was for the Government to survey and sell the land at a rate that would maintain land values high enough to be unaffordable for labourers and journeymen.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Funds raised from the sale of land were to be used to bring out working-class emigrants, who would have to work hard for the monied settlers to ever afford their own land.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] As a result of this policy, Adelaide does not share the convict settlement history of other Australian cities like Sydney, Brisbane and Hobart.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] As it was believed that in a colony of free settlers there would be little crime, no provision was made for a gaol in Colonel Light's 1837 plan.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] But by mid-1837 the *South Australian Register* was warning of escaped convicts from New South Wales and tenders for a temporary gaol were sought.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Following a burglary, a murder, and two attempted murders in Adelaide during March 1838, Governor Hindmarsh created the South Australian Police Force (now the South Australia Police) in April 1838 under 21-year-old Henry Inman.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The first sheriff, Samuel Smart, was wounded during a robbery, and on 2 May 1838 one of the offenders, Michael Magee, became the first person to be hanged in South Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] William Baker Ashton was appointed governor of the temporary gaol in 1839, and in 1840 George Strickland Kingston was commissioned to design Adelaide's new gaol.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Construction of Adelaide Gaol commenced in 1841.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early history was marked by economic uncertainty and questionable leadership.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The first governor of South Australia, John Hindmarsh, clashed frequently with others, in particular the Resident Commissioner, James Hurtle Fisher.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The rural area surrounding Adelaide was surveyed by Light in preparation to sell a total of over 405 km2 (156 sq mi) of land.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's early economy started to get on its feet in 1838 with the arrival of livestock from Victoria, New South Wales and Tasmania.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Wool production provided an early basis for the South Australian economy.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] By 1860, wheat farms had been established from Encounter Bay in the south to Clare in the north.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] He was criticised for his response to the Maria massacre.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Gawler was recalled and replaced by George Edward Grey in 1841.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Grey slashed public expenditure against heavy opposition, although its impact was negligible at this point: silver was discovered in Glen Osmond that year, agriculture was well underway, and other mines sprung up all over the state, aiding Adelaide's commercial development.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The city exported meat, wool, wine, fruit and wheat by the time Grey left in 1845, contrasting with a low point in 1842 when one-third of Adelaide houses were abandoned.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Trade links with the rest of the Australian states were established after the Murray River was successfully navigated in 1853 by Francis Cadell, an Adelaide resident.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] South Australia became a self-governing colony in 1856 with the ratification of a new constitution by the British parliament.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Secret ballots were introduced, and a bicameral parliament was elected on 9 March 1857, by which time 109,917 people lived in the province.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In 1860, the Thorndon Park reservoir was opened, providing an alternative water source to the now turbid River Torrens.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Gas street lighting was implemented in 1867, the University of Adelaide was founded in 1874, the South Australian Art Gallery opened in 1881 and the Happy Valley Reservoir opened in 1896.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In the 1890s Australia was affected by a severe economic depression, ending a hectic era of land booms and tumultuous expansionism.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Financial institutions in Melbourne and banks in Sydney closed.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The national fertility rate fell and immigration was reduced to a trickle.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The value of South Australia's exports nearly halved.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Drought and poor harvests from 1884 compounded the problems, with some families leaving for Western Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was not as badly hit as the larger gold-rush cities of Sydney and Melbourne, and silver and lead discoveries at Broken Hill provided some relief.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Only one year of deficit was recorded, but the price paid was retrenchments and lean public spending.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Wine and copper were the only industries not to suffer a downturn.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was Australia's third largest city for most of the 20th century.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Electric street lighting was introduced in 1900 and electric trams were transporting passengers in 1909.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] 28,000 men were sent to fight in World War I.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Crowley examined the reports of visitors in the early 20th century, noting that "many visitors to Adelaide admired the foresighted planning of its founders", as well as pondering the riches of the young city.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide enjoyed a postwar boom, entering a time of relative prosperity.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Its population grew, and it became the third most populous metropolitan area in the country, after Sydney and Melbourne.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Its prosperity was short-lived, with the return of droughts and the Great Depression of the 1930s.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] It later returned to fortune under strong government leadership.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Secondary industries helped reduce the state's dependence on primary industries.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] World War II brought industrial stimulus and diversification to Adelaide under the Playford Government, which advocated Adelaide as a safe place for manufacturing due to its less vulnerable location.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Shipbuilding was expanded at the nearby port of Whyalla.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The South Australian Government in this period built on former wartime manufacturing industries but neglected cultural facilities which meant South Australia's economy lagged behind.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] International manufacturers like Holden and Chrysler made use of these factories around the Adelaide area in suburbs like Elizabeth, completing its transformation from an agricultural service centre to a 20th-century motor city.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Mannum–Adelaide pipeline brought River Murray water to Adelaide in 1955 and an airport opened at West Beach in 1955.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Flinders University and the Flinders Medical Centre were established in the 1960s at Bedford Park, south of the city.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Today, Flinders Medical Centre is one of the largest teaching hospitals in South Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In the post-war years around the early 1960s, Adelaide was surpassed by Brisbane as Australia's third largest city.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Dunstan Governments of the 1970s saw something of an Adelaide "cultural revival", establishing a wide array of social reforms.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The city became noted for its progressivism as South Australia became the first Australian state or territory to decriminalise homosexuality between consenting adults in 1975.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide became a centre for the arts, building upon the biennial "Adelaide Festival of Arts" that commenced in 1960.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The State Bank collapsed in 1991 during an economic recession.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The effects lasted until 2004, when Standard & Poor's reinstated South Australia's AAA credit rating.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's tallest building, completed in 2020, is called the Adelaidean and is located at 11 Frome Street.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In the early years of the 21st century, a significant increase in the state government's spending on Adelaide's infrastructure occurred.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Rann government invested A$535 million in a major upgrade of the Adelaide Oval to enable Australian Football League to be played in the city centre and more than A$2 billion to build a new Royal Adelaide Hospital on land adjacent to the Adelaide Railway Station.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Glenelg tramline was extended through the city to Hindmarsh down to East Terrace and the suburban railway line extended south to Seaford.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Following a period of stagnation in the 1990s and 2000s, Adelaide began several major developments and redevelopments.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Convention Centre was redeveloped and expanded at a cost of A$350 million beginning in 2012.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The government invested more than A$2 billion to build a desalination plant, powered by renewable energy, as an "insurance policy" against droughts affecting Adelaide's water supply.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Festival, Fringe, and Womadelaide became annual events.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is north of the Fleurieu Peninsula, on the Adelaide Plains between the Gulf St Vincent and the relatively low-lying Mount Lofty Ranges (Mount Lofty, the highest point, is 710 metres above sea level).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The city stretches 20 km (12 mi) from the coast to the foothills, and 90 km (56 mi) from Gawler at its northern extent to Sellicks Beach in the south.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The city sits at an average elevation of 50 metres (160 ft) above sea level.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Mount Lofty, east of the Adelaide metropolitan region in the Adelaide Hills at an elevation of 727 metres (2,385 ft), is the tallest point of the city and in the state south of Burra.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The city borders the Temperate Grassland of South Australia in the east, an endangered vegetation community.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Much of Adelaide was bushland before British settlement, with some variation – sandhills, swamps and marshlands were prevalent around the coast.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The loss of the sandhills to urban development had a particularly destructive effect on the coastline due to erosion.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Where practical, the government has implemented programs to rebuild and vegetate sandhills at several of Adelaide's beachside suburbs.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Tennyson Dunes is the largest contiguous, tertiary dune system contained entirely within Metropolitan Adelaide, providing refuge for a variety of remnant species formerly found along the entire coastline.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Much of the original vegetation has been cleared with what is left to be found in reserves such as the Cleland National Park and Belair National Park.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] A number of creeks and rivers flow through the Adelaide region.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The largest are the Torrens and Onkaparinga catchments.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide relies on its many reservoirs for water supply with the Happy Valley Reservoir supplying around 40% and the much larger Mount Bold Reservoir 10% of Adelaide's domestic requirements respectively.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide and its surrounding area is one of the most seismically active regions in Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] On 1 March 1954 at 3:40 am Adelaide experienced its largest recorded earthquake to date, with the epicentre 12 km from the city centre at Darlington, and a reported magnitude of 5.6.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Most of the Adelaide metropolitan area lies in the downthrown St Vincent Basin and its embayments, including the Adelaide Plains Sub-basin, and the Golden Grove, Noarlunga and Willunga Embayments.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] These basins contain deposits of Tertiary marine and non-marine sands and limestones, which form important aquifers.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a planned city, designed by the first Surveyor-General of South Australia, Colonel William Light.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] His plan, sometimes referred to as "Light's Vision" (also the name of a statue of him on Montefiore Hill), arranged Adelaide in a grid, with five squares in the Adelaide city centre and a ring of parks, known as the Adelaide Parklands, surrounding it.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Light's selection of the location for the city was initially unpopular with the early settlers, as well as South Australia's first governor, John Hindmarsh, due to its distance from the harbour at Port Adelaide, and the lack of fresh water there.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Light successfully persisted with his choice of location against this initial opposition.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The benefits of Light's design are numerous: Adelaide has had wide multi-lane roads from its beginning, an easily navigable cardinal direction grid layout and an expansive green ring around the city centre.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] There are two sets of ring roads in Adelaide that have resulted from the original design.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The inner ring route (A21) borders the parklands, and the outer route (A3/A13/A16/A17) completely bypasses the inner city via (in clockwise order) Grand Junction Road, Hampstead Road, Ascot Avenue, Portrush Road, Cross Road and South Road.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Suburban expansion has to some extent outgrown Light's original plan.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Numerous former outlying villages and "country towns", as well as the satellite city of Elizabeth, have been enveloped by its suburban sprawl.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Expanding developments in the Adelaide Hills region led to the construction of the South Eastern Freeway to cope with growth, which has subsequently led to new developments and further improvements to that transport corridor.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Similarly, the booming development in Adelaide's South led to the construction of the Southern Expressway.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] New roads are not the only transport infrastructure developed to cope with the urban growth.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The O-Bahn Busway and Adelaide Metro are examples of a unique solution to Tea Tree Gully's transport woes in the 1980s.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The development of the nearby suburb of Golden Grove in the late 1980s followed a planned approach to urban growth.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In the 1960s, a Metropolitan Adelaide Transport Study Plan was proposed to cater for the future growth of the city.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The plan involved the construction of freeways, expressways and the upgrade of certain aspects of the public transport system.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The then premier Steele Hall approved many parts of the plan and the government went as far as purchasing land for the project.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The later Labor government elected under Don Dunstan shelved the plan, but allowed the purchased land to remain vacant, should the future need for freeways arise.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In 1980, the Liberal party won government and premier David Tonkin committed his government to selling off the land acquired for the MATS plan, ensuring that even when needs changed, the construction of most MATS-proposed freeways would be impractical.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Some parts of this land have been used for transport, (e.g. the O-Bahn Busway and Southern Expressway), while most has been progressively subdivided for residential use.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In 2008, the SA Government announced plans for a network of transport-oriented developments across the Adelaide metropolitan area and purchased a 10 hectare industrial site at Bowden for $52.5 million as the first of these developments.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Historically, Adelaide's suburban residential areas have been characterised by single-storey detached houses built on 1,000-square-metre (1⁄4-acre) blocks.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] A relative lack of suitable, locally available timber for construction purposes led to the early development of a brick-making industry, as well as the use of stone, for houses and other buildings.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] By 1891, 68% of houses were built of stone, 15% of timber, and 10% of brick, with brick also being widely used in stone houses for quoins, door and window surrounds, and chimneys and fireplaces.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] There is a wide variety in the styles of these houses.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Until the 1960s, most of the more substantial houses were built of red brick, though many front walls were of ornamental stone.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Then cream bricks became fashionable, and in the 1970s, deep red and brown bricks became popular.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Until the 1970s, roofs tended to be clad with (painted) corrugated iron or cement or clay tiles, usually red "terracotta".
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Since then, Colorbond corrugated steel has dominated.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Up to the 1970s, most houses were of "double brick" construction on concrete footings, with timber floors laid on joists supported by "dwarf walls".
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The use of precast concrete panels for floor and wall construction has also increased.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In addition to this, a significant factor in Adelaide's suburban history is the role of the South Australian Housing Trust.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has a hot-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csa*) under the Köppen climate classification.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The city has hot, dry summers and cool winters with moderate rainfall.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Most rain falls in the winter months, leading to the suggestion that the climate be classified as a "cold monsoon".
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Rainfall is unreliable, light and infrequent throughout summer, although heavy falls can occur.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The winter has fairly reliable rainfall with June being the wettest month of the year, averaging around 80 mm.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Frosts are occasional, with the most notable occurrences in 1908 and 1982.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is a windy city with significant wind chill in winter, which makes the temperature seem colder than it actually is.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Snowfall in the metropolitan area is extremely rare, although light and sporadic falls in the nearby hills and at Mount Lofty occur during winter.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Dewpoints in the summer typically range from 8 to 10 °C (46 to 50 °F).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] There are usually several days in summer where the temperature reaches 40.0 °C (104.0 °F) or above.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] While conditions vary from year-to-year, a warming trend has been increasing in recent years, and with drought conditions experienced in SA in 2024−25, Adelaide has had to rely on desalination to augment its water supply.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The city features 90.6 clear days annually.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The average sea temperature ranges from 13.7 °C (56.7 °F) in August to 21.2 °C (70.2 °F) in February.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was consistently ranked in the world's 10 most liveable cities through the 2010s by The Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In June 2021, *The Economist* ranked Adelaide the third most liveable city in the world, behind Auckland and Osaka.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In June 2023, Adelaide was ranked the twelfth most liveable city in the world by the Economist Intelligence Unit.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In December 2021, Adelaide was named the world's second National Park City, after the state government had lobbied for this title.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] It was ranked the most liveable city in Australia by the Property Council of Australia, based on surveys of residents' views of their own city, between 2010 and 2013, dropping to second place in 2014.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide, as the capital of South Australia, is the seat of the Government of South Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The bicameral Parliament of South Australia consists of the lower house known as the House of Assembly and the upper house known as the Legislative Council.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] General elections are held every four years, the last being the 2022 South Australian state election.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] As Adelaide is South Australia's capital and most populous city, the State Government co-operates extensively with the City of Adelaide.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In 2006, the Ministry for the City of Adelaide was created to facilitate the State Government's collaboration with the Adelaide City Council and the Lord Mayor to improve Adelaide's image.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The State Parliament's Capital City Committee is also involved in the governance of the City of Adelaide, being primarily concerned with the planning of Adelaide's urban development and growth.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Reflecting South Australia's status as Australia's most centralised state, Adelaide elects a substantial majority of the South Australian House of Assembly.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Of the 47 seats in the chamber, 34 seats (three-quarters of the legislature) are based in Adelaide, and two rural seats include Adelaide suburbs.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide metropolitan area is divided between nineteen local government areas.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] At its centre, the City of Adelaide administers the Adelaide city centre, North Adelaide, and the surrounding Adelaide Parklands.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] It is the oldest municipal authority in Australia and was established in 1840, when Adelaide and Australia's first mayor, James Hurtle Fisher, was elected.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] From 1919 onwards, the city has had a Lord Mayor, the current being Lord Mayor *The Right Honourable* Jane Lomax-Smith.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants are known as Adelaideans.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Compared with Australia's other state capitals, Adelaide is growing at a rate similar to Sydney and Hobart (see List of cities in Australia by population).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In 2024, it had a metropolitan population (including suburbs) of 1,469,163, making it Australia's fifth-largest city.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] 77% of the population of South Australia are residents of the Adelaide metropolitan area, making South Australia one of the most centralised states.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Major areas of population growth in recent years have been in outer suburbs such as Mawson Lakes and Golden Grove.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's inhabitants occupy 366,912 houses, 57,695 semi-detached, row terrace or town houses and 49,413 flats, units or apartments.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] About one sixth (17.1%) of the population had university qualifications.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The number of Adelaideans with vocational qualifications (such as tradespersons) fell from 62.1% of the labour force in the 1991 census to 52.4% in the 2001 census.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is aging more rapidly than other Australian capital cities.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] More than a quarter (27.5%) of Adelaide's population is aged 55 years or older, in comparison to the national average of 25.6%.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide has the lowest number of children (under-15-year-olds), who comprised 17.7% of the population, compared to the national average of 19.3%.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Overseas-born Adelaideans composed 31.3% of the total population at the 2021 census.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The five largest groups of overseas-born were from England (5.7%), India (3.1%), Mainland China (1.8%), Vietnam (1.2%) and Italy (1.1%).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Suburbs including Newton, Payneham and Campbelltown in the east and Torrensville, West Lakes and Fulham to the west, have large Greek and Italian communities.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Italian consulate is located in the western suburb of Hindmarsh.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Large Vietnamese populations are settled in the north-western suburbs of Woodville, Kilkenny, Pennington, Mansfield Park and Athol Park and also Parafield Gardens and Pooraka in Adelaide's north.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Migrants from India and Sri Lanka have settled into inner suburban areas of Adelaide including the inner northern suburbs of Blair Athol, Kilburn and Enfield and the inner southern suburbs of Plympton, Park Holme and Kurralta Park.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Suburbs such as Para Hills, Salisbury, Ingle Farm and Blair Athol in the north and Findon, West Croydon and Seaton and other Western suburbs have sizeable Afghan communities.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Chinese migrants favour settling in the eastern and north eastern suburbs including Kensington Gardens, Greenacres, Modbury and Golden Grove.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Mawson Lakes has a large international student population, due to its proximity to the University of South Australia campus.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] At the 2021 census, 1.7% of Adelaide's population identified as being Indigenous — Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] At the 2016 census, 75.4% of the population spoke English at home.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The other languages most commonly spoken at home were Italian (2.1%), Standard Mandarin (2.1%), Greek (1.7%) Vietnamese (1.4%), and Cantonese (0.7%).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Kaurna language, spoken by the area's original inhabitants, had no living speakers in the middle of the 20th century, but since the 1990s there has been a sustained revival effort from academics and Kaurna elders.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide was founded on a vision of religious tolerance that attracted a wide variety of religious practitioners.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] This led to it being known as *The City of Churches*.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] But approximately 28% of the population expressed no religious affiliation in the 2011 Census, compared with the national average of 22.3%, making Adelaide one of Australia's least religious cities.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] According to 2021 census, 39.8% of the population of Adelaide identify as Christian, with the largest denominations being Catholic (16.4%), Anglican (7.0%), Uniting Church (3.9%) and Greek Orthodox (2.4%).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Non-Christian faith communities, representing 9.5% from Adelaide's population, include Islam (2.8%), Hinduism (2.7%) and Buddhism (2.3%).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Jewish community of the city dates back to 1840.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Eight years later, 58 Jews lived in the city.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] A synagogue was built in 1871, when 435 Jews lived in the city.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Many took part in the city councils, such as Judah Moss Solomon (1852–66).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Three Jews have been elected to the position of city mayor.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In 1968, the Jewish population of Adelaide numbered about 1,200; in 2001, according to the Australian census, 979 persons declared themselves to be Jewish by religion.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In 2011, over 1,000 Jews were living in the city, served by an Orthodox synagogue, Adelaide Hebrew Congregation and a Reform synagogue, **Beit Shalom**, in addition to a virtual Jewish museum.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Massada College, a Jewish day school opened in the city in 1976 and closed in 2011.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Holocaust Museum and Andrew Steiner Education Centre opened in 2020.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The "Afghan" community in Australia first became established in the 1860s when camels and their Pathan, Punjabi, Baluchi and Sindhi handlers began to be used to open up settlement in the continent's arid interior.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Until eventually superseded by the advent of the railways and motor vehicles, camels played an invaluable economic and social role in transporting heavy loads of goods to and from isolated settlements and mines.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] This is acknowledged by the name of The Ghan, the passenger train operating between Adelaide, Alice Springs, and Darwin.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Central Adelaide Mosque is regarded as Australia's oldest permanent mosque; an earlier mosque at Marree in northern South Australia, dating from 1861 to 1862 and subsequently abandoned or demolished, has now been rebuilt.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] South Australia's largest employment sectors are health care and social assistance, surpassing manufacturing in SA as the largest employer since 2006–07.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In 2009–10, manufacturing in SA had average annual employment of 83,700 persons compared with 103,300 for health care and social assistance.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Health care and social assistance represented nearly 13% of the state average annual employment.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Adelaide Hills wine region is an iconic and viable economic region for both the state and country in terms of wine production and sale.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The retail trade is the second largest employer in SA (2009–10), with over 91,900 jobs, and 12 per cent of the state workforce.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Manufacturing, defence technology, high-tech electronic systems and research, commodity export and corresponding service industries all play a role in the SA economy.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Almost half of all cars produced in Australia were made in Adelaide at the Holden Elizabeth Plant in Elizabeth.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The site ceased operating in November 2017.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The collapse of the State Bank in 1992 resulted in large levels of state public debt (as much as A$4 billion).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The collapse meant that successive governments enacted lean budgets, cutting spending, which was a setback to the further economic development of the city and state.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] As of January 2026, the government has an AA+ credit rating.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The global media conglomerate News Corporation was founded in, and until 2004 incorporated in, Adelaide, and the city is still considered the Corporation's "spiritual" home by its founder, Rupert Murdoch.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Australia's largest oil company, Santos, prominent South Australian brewery, Coopers, and national retailer Harris Scarfe also call Adelaide their home.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] In 2018, at which time more than 80 organisations employed 800 people in the space sector in South Australia, Adelaide was chosen for the headquarters of a new Australian Space Agency.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] It is working to triple the size of the Australian space industry and create 20,000 new jobs by 2030.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide is home to a large proportion of Australia's defence industries, which contribute over A$1 billion to South Australia's Gross State Product.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Others, such as Saab Systems and Raytheon, are in or near Technology Park.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] ASC Pty Ltd, is based in the industrial suburb of Osborne and is also a part of Technology Park.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] South Australia was charged with constructing Australia's *Collins*-class submarines and more recently the A$6 billion contract to construct the Royal Australian Navy's new air-warfare destroyers.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] As of November 2015, Greater Adelaide had an unemployment rate of 7.4% with a youth unemployment rate of 15%.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The median weekly individual income for people aged 15 years and over was $447 per week in 2006, compared with $466 nationally.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The median family income was $1,137 per week, compared with $1,171 nationally.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Adelaide's housing and living costs are substantially lower than that of other Australian cities, with housing being notably cheaper.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The median Adelaide house price is half that of Sydney and two-thirds that of Melbourne.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The three-month trend unemployment rate to March 2007 was 6.2%.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] The Northern suburbs' unemployment rate is disproportionately higher than the other regions of Adelaide at 8.3%, while the East and South are lower than the Adelaide average at 4.9% and 5.0% respectively.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Over the decade March 2001 – March 2010, Metropolitan Adelaide median house prices approximately tripled.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] 11%p.a. compounding) In the five years March 2007 – March 2012, prices increased by approx.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] March 2012 – March 2017 saw a further increase of 19% – approx.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] no longer release a median house price for the Adelaide Metropolitan area, so figures retrieved are from Dept of the Premier and Cabinet.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Each quarter, The Alternative and Direct Investment Securities Association (ADISA) publishes a list of median house sale prices by suburb and Local Government Area.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p01] Quarterly Reports for the last two years can be found on the REISA website.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Education forms an increasingly important part of the city's economy, with the South Australian Government and educational institutions attempting to position Adelaide as "Australia's education hub" and marketing it as a "Learning City".
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The number of international students studying in Adelaide has increased rapidly in recent years to 30,726 in 2015, of which 1,824 were secondary school students.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the birthplace of three Nobel laureates, more than any other Australian city: physicist William Lawrence Bragg and pathologists Howard Florey and Robin Warren, all of whom completed secondary and tertiary education at St Peter's College and the University of Adelaide.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also the hometown of mathematician Terence Tao.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] There are two systems of primary and secondary schools, a public system operated by the South Australian Government's Department for Education, and a private system of independent and Catholic schools.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] South Australian schools provide education under the Australian Curriculum for reception to Year 10 students.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In Years 10 to 12, students study for the South Australian Certificate of Education (SACE).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] They have the option of incorporating vocational education and training (VET) courses or a flexible learning option (FLO).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has 24 schools that use International Baccalaureate programs as an alternative to the Australian Curriculum or SACE.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] These programs include the IB Primary Years Programme, the IB Middle Years Programme, and the IB Diploma Programme.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] For South Australian students who cannot attend a traditional school, including students who live in rural or remote areas, the state government runs the Open Access College (OAC), which provides virtual teaching.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The OAC has a campus in Marden which caters to students from reception to Year 12 and adults who haven't been able to complete their SACE.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Guardians are also able to apply for their child to be educated from home as long as they provide an education program which meets the same requirements as the Australian Curriculum as well as opportunities for social interaction.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] There are two public universities local to Adelaide, as well as one private university and three constituent colleges of foreign universities.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Flinders University of South Australia, Adelaide University and Torrens University Australia—part of the Laureate International Universities are based in Adelaide.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The University of Adelaide was ranked in the top 150 universities worldwide.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Flinders ranked in the top 250 and Uni SA in the top 300.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Torrens University Australia is part of an international network of over 70 higher education institutions in more than 30 countries worldwide.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide University is a recent amalgamation between the University of Adelaide and the University of South Australia, ranked in the top 150 globally and top 10 nationally.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Today, it stands as Australia's third-oldest university and a member of the leading "Group of Eight".
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The merged university has over 64,000 students and two main campuses on North Terrace, with many other campuses across South Australia, including in Whyalla and Mount Gambier.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The two universities had multiple proposals to merge into a single university.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] A proposal in 2018 failed due to uncertainty as to the new name and leadership of the merged university.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2022, the universities announced a new merger proposal, with the name and leadership issues settled and support from the South Australian government.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Flinders University, with 25,184 students, is based in the southern suburb of Bedford Park, alongside the Flinders Medical Centre, with additional campuses in neighbouring Tonsley and in Victoria Square in the city centre.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2024, the University of the Sunshine Coast opened a new campus in Adelaide where undergraduate and master's courses in ICT and business are offered.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of Divinity is at Brooklyn Park.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] There are several South Australian TAFE (Technical and Further Education) campuses in the metropolitan area that provide a range of vocational education and training.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide College of the Arts, as a school of TAFE SA, provides nationally recognised training in visual and performing arts.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Workers' Educational Association of South Australia (WEA-SA) is an independent not-for-profit adult education organisation based in Adelaide.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Established in 1913, it is one of Australia's longest running providers of community-based adult learning.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] WEA-SA delivers short courses, lectures, cultural programs, travel and interest clubs designed to promote lifelong learning.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] StudyAdelaide, a collaboration between the South Australian government and the tertiary education sector, maintains an on-line list of schools, universities, and higher education institutions in SA.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In addition to the universities, Adelaide is home to research institutes, including the Royal Institution of Australia, established in 2009 as a counterpart to the two-hundred-year-old Royal Institution of Great Britain.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] While established as a British province, and very much English in terms of its culture, Adelaide attracted immigrants from other parts of Europe early on, including German and other European non-conformists escaping religious persecution.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The first German Lutherans arrived in 1838, bringing with them the vine cuttings that they used to found the acclaimed wineries of the Barossa Valley.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Royal Adelaide Show is an annual agricultural show and state fair, established in 1839 and now a huge event held in the Adelaide Showground annually.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's arts scene flourished in the 1960s and 1970s with the support of successive premiers from both major political parties.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The renowned Adelaide Festival of Arts was established in 1960 under Thomas Playford, which in the same year spawned an unofficial uncurated series of performances and exhibits which grew into the Adelaide Fringe.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Construction of the Adelaide Festival Centre began under Steele Hall in 1970 and was completed under the subsequent government of Don Dunstan, who also established the South Australian Film Corporation in 1972 and the State Opera of South Australia in 1976.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] With the Festival, the Fringe, WOMADelaide, Writers' Week and the Adelaide 500 street motor racing event (along with evening music concerts) all happening in early March, the period became known colloquially as "Mad March".
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2014, Ghil'ad Zuckermann founded the Adelaide Language Festival.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] There are many international cultural fairs, most notably the German Schützenfest and Greek Glendi.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide holds an annual Christmas pageant, the world's largest Christmas parade.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] As the state capital, Adelaide has a great number of cultural institutions, many of them along the boulevard of North Terrace.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Art Gallery of South Australia, with about 35,000 works, holds Australia's second largest state-based collection.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adjacent are the South Australian Museum and State Library of South Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Botanic Garden, National Wine Centre and Tandanya National Aboriginal Cultural Institute are nearby in the East End of the city.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In the back of the State Library lies the Migration Museum, Australia's oldest museum of its kind.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Further west, the Lion Arts Centre is home to ACE Open, which showcases contemporary art; Dance Hub SA; and other studios and arts industry spaces.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Mercury Cinema and the JamFactory ceramics and design gallery are just around the corner.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Festival Centre (which includes the Dunstan Playhouse, Festival Theatre and Space Theatre), on the banks of the Torrens, is the focal point for much of the cultural activity in the city and home to the State Theatre Company of South Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Other live music and theatre venues include the Adelaide Entertainment Centre; Adelaide Oval; Memorial Drive Park; Thebarton Theatre; Adelaide Town Hall; Her Majesty's Theatre; Queen's Theatre; Holden Street Theatres; and the Hopgood Theatre.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Lion Arts Factory, within the Lion Arts Centre, hosts contemporary music in a wide range of genres, as does "The Gov" in Hindmarsh.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The city also has numerous smaller theatres, pubs and cabaret bars which host performances.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2015, it was said that there were now more live music venues per capita in Adelaide than any other capital city in the southern hemisphere, *Lonely Planet* labelled Adelaide "Australia's live music city", and the city was recognised as a "City of Music" by the UNESCO Creative Cities Network.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Although there were many pubs hosting live music in the CBD in past, the number has slowly diminished.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Grace Emily on Waymouth Street, which was refurbished as a live music venue around 2000, is popular with musicians and patrons alike.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Crown & Anchor ("the Cranker") was saved from demolition in 2024 after a vigorous campaign by the public as well as many musicians and politicians.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] New legislation passed on 11 September 2024 designates the entire Adelaide CBD as a "live music venue area", and gives protection to selected live music venues.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In addition to its own WOMAD (WOMADelaide), Adelaide has attracted several touring music festivals, including Creamfields, Laneway, and Groovin' (some since defunct).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has produced musical groups and individuals who have achieved national and international fame.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Noted rocker Jimmy Barnes (formerly lead vocalist with Cold Chisel) spent most of his youth in the northern suburb of Elizabeth.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Australian singer-songwriter Paul Kelly grew up in Adelaide and was head prefect at Rostrevor College.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The first *Australian Idol* winner, Guy Sebastian, hails from the north-eastern suburb of Golden Grove.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] All of the five Australian national television networks broadcast both high-definition digital and standard-definition digital television services in Adelaide.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] They share three transmission towers on the ridge near the summit of Mount Lofty.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] There are two other transmission sites at 25 Grenfell Street, Adelaide and Elizabeth Downs.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The two government-funded stations are run by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC South Australia) and the Special Broadcasting Service (SBS).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Seven Network and Network Ten both own their Adelaide stations (SAS-7 and ADS-10 respectively).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's NWS-9 is part of the Nine Network.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has a community television station, Channel 44.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] As part of a nationwide phase-out of analogue television in Australia, Adelaide's analogue television service was shut down on 2 April 2013.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] There are 20 radio stations that serve the metropolitan area, as well as four stations that serve only parts of the metropolitan area; six commercial stations, six community stations, six national stations and two narrowcast stations.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] DAB+ digital radio has been broadcasting in metropolitan Adelaide since 20 May 2009, and currently offers a choice of 41 stations all operated by the existing licensed radio broadcasters, which includes high-quality simulcast of all AM and FM stations.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The main sports played professionally in Adelaide are Australian Rules football, soccer, cricket, netball, and basketball.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is the home of two Australian Football League teams: the Adelaide Football Club and Port Adelaide Football Club, and one A-League soccer team, Adelaide United.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] A local Australian rules football league, the South Australian National Football League (SANFL), is made up of 10 teams from around Adelaide.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The SANFL has been in operation since 1877 when it began as the South Australian Football Association (SAFA) before changing its name to the SANFL in 1927.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The SANFL is the oldest surviving football league of any code played in Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Since completion of the upgrade, home games for Adelaide Crows and Port Adelaide now take place at Adelaide Oval.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Since 1884, Adelaide Oval has also hosted an international cricket test every summer, along with a number of One Day International cricket matches.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Memorial Drive Park, adjacent to the Adelaide Oval, used to host Davis Cup and other major tennis events, including the Australian Open and the Adelaide International.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's professional association football team, Adelaide United, play in the A-League.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Founded in 2003, their home ground is Coopers Stadium, which has a capacity of 16,500 and is one of the few purpose-built soccer stadia in Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Prior to United's foundation, Adelaide City and West Adelaide represented the city in the National Soccer League.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The two sides, which contest the Adelaide derby against one another, now play in the National Premier Leagues South Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] For two years, 1997 and 1998, Adelaide was represented in Australia's top level rugby league, after the New South Wales Rugby League had played a single game per season at the Adelaide Oval for five years starting in 1991.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide Rams were formed and played in the breakaway Super League (SL) competition in 1997 before moving to the new National Rugby League in 1998.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Initially playing at the Adelaide Oval, the club moved to the more suitable Hindmarsh Stadium late in the 1998 season.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] As part of a peace deal with the Australian Rugby League to end the Super League war, the club's owners News Limited (who were also owners of the SL) suddenly closed the club only weeks before the start of the 1999 season.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has two professional basketball teams, the men's team being the Adelaide 36ers which plays in the National Basketball League (NBL) and the women's team, the Adelaide Lightning which plays in the Women's National Basketball League (WNBL).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide 36ers play at the Adelaide Entertainment Centre while the Adelaide Lightning play at the Adelaide Arena (Previously Titanium Security Arena).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide has a professional netball team, the Adelaide Thunderbirds, which plays in the national netball competition, the Super Netball championship, with home games played at Netball SA Stadium.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Thunderbirds occasionally play games or finals at the Titanium Security Arena, while international netball matches are usually played at the 10,500 seat Adelaide Entertainment Centre.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Titanium Security Arena has a capacity of 8,000 and is the largest purpose-built basketball stadium in Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Since 1999 Adelaide and its surrounding areas have hosted the Tour Down Under bicycle race, organised and directed by Adelaide-based Michael Turtur.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Turtur won an Olympic gold medal for Australia in the 4000 m team pursuit at the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Tour Down Under is the largest cycling event outside Europe and was the first event outside Europe to be granted UCI ProTour status.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The 2024 Women's Tour Down Under cycle stage race was held in and around Adelaide, South Australia from 12 to 14 January 2024.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide maintains a franchise in the Australian Baseball League, the Adelaide Giants.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] They have been playing since 2009, and their home stadium (until 2016) was Norwood Oval.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] From 2016 the team moved to the Diamond Sports Stadium located near the Adelaide International Airport due to renovations at Norwood.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide also has an ice hockey team, Adelaide Adrenaline in the Australian Ice Hockey League (AIHL).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] It was national champions in 2009 and plays its games at the IceArenA.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Australian Grand Prix for World Championship Formula One racing was hosted by Adelaide from 1985 to 1995 on the Adelaide Street Circuit which was laid out in the city's East End as well as the eastern parklands including the Victoria Park Racecourse.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Grand Prix became a source of pride, and losing the event to Melbourne in a surprise announcement in mid-1993 left a void that has since been filled with the Adelaide 500 for V8 Supercar racing, held on a modified version of the same street circuit.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Classic Adelaide, a rally of classic sporting vehicles, is also held in the city and its surrounds.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide formerly had three horse racing venues.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Victoria Park, Cheltenham Park Racecourse, both of which have now closed, and Morphettville Racecourse that remains the home of the South Australian Jockey Club.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] It also has Globe Derby Park for Harness racing that opened in 1969, and by 1973 had become Adelaide's premier harness racing venue taking over from the Wayville Showgrounds, as well as Greyhound Park for greyhound racing that opened in 1972.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The World Solar Challenge race attracts teams from around the world, most of which are fielded by universities or corporations, although some are fielded by high schools.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The race has a 20-years' history spanning nine races, with the inaugural event taking place in 1987.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide hosted the 2012 World Bowls Championships at Lockleys Bowling Club, becoming the third city in the world to have held the championships twice, having previously hosted the event in 1996.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Dirt track speedway is also popular in Adelaide with three operating speedways.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Motorsport Park, located adjacent to the Adelaide International Raceway road racing circuit at Virginia (24 km (15 mi) north of the city centre) has been in continuous operation since 1979 after the closure of the popular Rowley Park Speedway.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Gillman Speedway located in the semi-industrial suburb of Gillman, has been in operation since 1998 and caters to Motorcycle speedway and Sidecars, while the Sidewinders Speedway located in Wingfield is also a motorcycle speedway dedicated to Under-16 riders and has been in operation since 1978.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2016, backed by South Australia's Peregrine Corporation opened up a multi-purpose facility; a state-of-the-art motorsporting park and a hotel alongside its newer OTR service station outside a small township of Tailem Bend currently named The Bend Motorsport Park.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Design for thrill seekers and rev-heads the facility currently host South Australia's second Supercars motoring event during a round in August.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is home to the Great Southern Slam, the world's largest roller derby tournament.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The tournament has been held biennially over Australia's Queen's Birthday holiday weekend since 2010.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2014, and 2016 the tournament featured 45 teams playing in two divisions.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2018, the tournament has expanded to 48 teams competing in three divisions.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Being centrally located on the Australian mainland, Adelaide forms a strategic transport hub for east–west and north–south routes.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The city itself has a metropolitan public transport system managed by and known as the Adelaide Metro.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Tramways were largely dismantled in the 1950s, but saw a revival in the 2010s with upgrades and extensions.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Road transport in Adelaide has historically been easier than many of the other Australian cities, with a well-defined city layout and wide multiple-lane roads from the beginning of its development.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide was known as a "twenty-minute city", with commuters having been able to travel from metropolitan outskirts to the city proper in roughly twenty minutes.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] However, such arterial roads often experience traffic congestion as the city grows.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has one freeway and four expressways.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The Adelaide metropolitan area has two commercial airports, Adelaide Airport and Parafield Airport.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide Airport, in Adelaide's south-western suburbs, serves almost 9 million passengers annually, with an extensive number of direct flight routes within Australia, as well as other destinations in Oceania, Asia and North America.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport, Adelaide's second airport 18 kilometres (11 miles) north of the city centre, is used for small aircraft, pilot training and recreational aviation purposes.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Parafield Airport served as Adelaide's main aerodrome until the opening of the Adelaide Airport in February 1955.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide is also home to a military airport, known as RAAF Base Edinburgh, located in the northern suburbs.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] It was built in 1955 in a joint initiative with the United Kingdom for weapon development.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's two largest hospitals are the Royal Adelaide Hospital (RAH) in Adelaide Parklands, a teaching hospital affiliated with the University of Adelaide (800 beds), and the Flinders Medical Centre (580 beds) at Bedford Park, affiliated with Flinders University.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The RAH also operates additional campuses for specialist care throughout the suburbs including the Hampstead Rehabilitation Centre (150 beds) at Northfield and the Glenside Campus (129 beds) for acute mental health services.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Other major public hospitals are the Women's and Children's Hospital (305 beds), at North Adelaide; the Queen Elizabeth Hospital (340 beds) at Woodville; Modbury Hospital (174 beds) at Modbury; and the Lyell McEwin Hospital (198 beds) at Elizabeth Vale.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Numerous private hospitals are also located throughout the city, with the largest operators being not-for-profits Adelaide Community Healthcare Alliance (three hospitals) and Calvary Care (four hospitals).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2017, the RAH was relocated from the city's East End to a new AU$2.3 billion facility built over former railyards in the West End.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] SAHMRI, with additional external funding, has built a $300 million second facility completed in 2024, which was intended to house the Australian Bragg Centre with Australia's first proton therapy unit.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Construction is underway for the Women's and Children's Hospital to be relocated to the precinct adjacent the RAH by 2030.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The largest provider of community health care within Adelaide is the not-for-profit Royal District Nursing Service, which provides out of hospital care and hospital avoidance care.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's energy requirements were originally met by the Adelaide Electric Supply Company, which was nationalised by the Playford government in 1946, becoming the Electricity Trust of South Australia (ETSA).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The electricity retail market was opened to competition in 2003 and although competition was expected to result in lower retail costs, prices increased by 23.7% in the market's first year.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2004, the privatisation was deemed to be a failure with consumers paying 60% more for their power and with the state government estimated to lose $3 billion in power generation net income in the first ten years of privatisation.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2012, the industry came under scrutiny for allegedly reducing supply by shutting down generators during periods of peak demand to force prices up.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Increased media attention also revealed that in 2009 the state government had approved a 46% increase in retail prices to cover expected increases in the costs of generation while generation costs had in fact fallen 35% by 2012.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] South Australia has the highest retail price for electricity in the country.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Privatisation led to competition from a variety of companies who now separately provide for the generation, transmission, distribution and retail sales of gas and electricity.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Electricity generation comes from a range of technologies and operators.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] ElectraNet operates the high-voltage electricity transmission network.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] SA Power Networks distributes electricity to end users.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The largest electricity and gas retailing companies are also the largest generating companies.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The largest fossil fuel power stations are the Torrens Island Power Station gas-fired plant operated by AGL Energy and the Pelican Point Power Station operated by Engie.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] South Australia also has wind and solar power and connections to the national grid.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Gas is supplied from the Moomba Gas Processing Plant in the Cooper Basin via the Moomba Adelaide Pipeline System and the SEAGas pipeline from Victoria.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2011, South Australia generated 18% of its electricity from wind power, and had 51% of the installed capacity of wind generators in Australia.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Due to almost universal blackouts within the city during September 2016, the state worked with Tesla to produce the world's largest electricity battery at Hornsdale Power Reserve which has increased that state's electrical security to the extent in which large blackouts are no longer an event.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The provision of water services is by the government-owned SA Water.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] Adelaide's water is supplied from its seven reservoirs: Mount Bold, Happy Valley, Myponga, Millbrook, Hope Valley, Little Para and South Para.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The yield from these reservoir catchments can be as little as 10% of the city's requirements (90GL per annum) in drought years and about 60% in average years.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The remaining demand is met by the pumping of water from the River Murray.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] A sea-water desalination plant capable of supplying 100GL per annum was built during the 2001–2009 drought; however, it operated at about 8% of its capacity until 2019.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In December 2018, the State and Federal Governments agreed to fund a $2m study to determine how the plant could be used to reduce reliance on river water, in an effort to help save the Murray River basin and mouth (including the Coorong) from further ecological damage.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] AdelaideFree WiFi is a citywide free Wi-Fi network covering most of the inner city areas of Adelaide, primarily the Adelaide CBD and Northern Adelaide precincts.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] It was officially launched at the Adelaide Central Markets on Tuesday 25 June 2014.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] It was originally provided by Internode with infrastructure provided by outdoor Cisco WiFi N access points attached to the top of lighting poles, as well as inside cafes and businesses across the city.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2023, a new agreement was reached between the City of Adelaide and TPG Telecom to replace the network infrastructure, improving network speed and coverage.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The City of Adelaide, was a 10 sail composite (timber planking on a wrought-iron frame) clipper.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] It was rescued from the mooring where it sank, as HMS Carrick, in Glasgow in 1991.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] In 2001 it was decided that the ship's name would be reverted to the City of Adelaide, formally renamed in 2013, and arrived in Port Adelaide on 3 February 2014.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] It was not until June 2024 that the ship was moved from the barge Bradley by Wallbridge Gilbert Aztec (WGA) to the current home on Dock 2, as the centerpiece of a planned village in Port Adelaide's inner harbour.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The ship is owned by the Clipper Ship City of Adelaide Ltd (CSCOAL).
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The STV One and All, a 42-metre two-masted square-rigged brigantine and the ketch *The Failie* are moored at McLaren Wharf.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] The City of Adelaide has been involved in the sister cities movement since 1972.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] As of 2023 it has long-term international partnership arrangements with five cities, known as sister cities, based on formal agreements between Adelaide and each city.
[src:algaculture/adelaide-p02] This allows collaboration in the cultural, educational, business, and technical spheres.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Water aeration is often required in water bodies that suffer from hypoxic or anoxic conditions, often caused by upstream human activities such as sewage discharges, agricultural run-off, or over-baiting a fishing lake.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Aeration can be achieved through the infusion of air into the bottom of the lake, lagoon or pond or by surface agitation from a fountain or spray-like device to allow for oxygen exchange at the surface and the release of gasses such as carbon dioxide, methane or hydrogen sulfide.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Decreased levels of dissolved oxygen (DO) is a major contributor to poor water quality.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Not only do fish and most other aquatic animals need oxygen, aerobic bacteria help decompose organic matter.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] When oxygen concentrations become low, anoxic conditions may develop which can decrease the ability of the water body to support life.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Any procedure by which oxygen is added to water can be considered a type of water aeration.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] There are many ways to aerate water, but these all fall into two broad areas – **surface aeration** and **subsurface aeration**.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] A variety of techniques and technologies are available for both approaches.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Natural aeration is a type of both sub-surface and surface aeration.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] It can occur through sub-surface aquatic plants.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Through the natural process of photosynthesis, water plants release oxygen into the water providing it with the oxygen necessary for fish to live and aerobic bacteria to break down excess nutrients.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Oxygen can be driven into the water when the wind disturbs the surface of the water body and natural aeration can also occur through a movement of water caused by an incoming stream, waterfall, or even a strong flood.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] In large water bodies in temperate climates, autumn turn-over can introduce oxygen rich water into the oxygen-poor hypolimnion.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] The low speed surface aerator is a device for biology aeration with high efficiency.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] These devices are often in steel protected by epoxy coating and generate high torque.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] The mixing of water volume is excellent.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] The common power is going from 1 up to 250kW per unit with an efficiency (SOE) around 2 kgO2/kw.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Low speed aerator are used mostly for biology plant aeration for water purification.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] The higher the diameter, the higher the SOE and mixing.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] A fountain consists of a means of spraying the water upwards into the air.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Typically this may be done using a motor that powers a rotating impeller.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] The impeller pumps water from the first few feet of the water and expels it into the air.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] This process utilizes air-water contact to transfer oxygen.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] As the water is propelled into the air, it breaks into small droplets.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Collectively, these small droplets have a large surface area through which oxygen can be transferred.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Upon return, these droplets mix with the rest of the water and thus transfer their oxygen back to the ecosystem.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Fountains are a popular method of providing surface aeration because of the aesthetic appearance that they offer.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] However, most fountains are unable to produce a large area of oxygenated water.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Also, running electricity through the water to the fountain can be a safety hazard.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Floating surface aerators work in a similar manner to fountains, but they do not offer the same aesthetic appearance.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] They extract water from the top 1–2 feet of the water body and utilize air-water contact to transfer oxygen.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Instead of propelling water into the air, they disrupt the water at the water surface.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Floating surface aerators are also powered by on-shore electricity.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] The effectiveness of a surface aerator is limited to a small area as they are unable to add circulation or oxygen to much more than a 3-metre radius.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] This circulation and oxygenating is then limited to the uppermost portion of the water column, often leaving the bottom portions unaffected.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Low speed surface aerators can also be installed on floats.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Paddlewheel aerators also utilize air-to-water contact to transfer oxygen from the air in the atmosphere to the water body.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] They are most often used in the aquaculture (rearing aquatic animals or cultivating aquatic plants for food) field.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Constructed of a hub with attached paddles, these aerators are usually powered by a tractor power take-off (PTO), a gas engine, or an electric motor.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Electricity forces the paddles to turn, churning the water and allowing oxygen transfer through air-water contact.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] As each new section of water is churned, it absorbs oxygen from the air and then, upon its return to the water, restores it to the water.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] In this regard paddlewheel aeration works very similarly to floating surface aerators.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Subsurface aeration seeks to release bubbles at the bottom of the water body and allow them to rise by the force of buoyancy.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] *Diffused aeration systems* utilize bubbles to aerate as well as mix the water.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Water displacement from the expulsion of bubbles will cause a mixing action to occur, and the contact between the water and the bubble will result in an oxygen transfer.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Subsurface aeration can be accomplished by the use of jet aerators, which aspirate air, by means of the Venturi principle, and inject the air into the liquid.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Coarse bubble aeration is a type of subsurface aeration wherein air is pumped from an on-shore air compressor. through a hose to a unit placed at the bottom of the water body.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] The unit expels *coarse bubbles* (more than 2mm in diameter), which release oxygen when they come into contact with the water, which also contributes to a mixing of the lake's stratified layers.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] With the release of large bubbles from the system, a turbulent displacement of water occurs which results in a mixing of the water.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] In comparison to other aeration techniques, coarse bubble aeration is very inefficient in the way of transferring oxygen.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] This is due to the large diameter and relatively small collective surface area of its bubbles.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Fine bubble aeration is an efficient way to transfer oxygen to a water body.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] A compressor on shore pumps air through a hose, which is connected to an underwater aeration unit.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Attached to the unit are a number of diffusers.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] These diffusers come in the shape of discs, plates, tubes or hoses constructed from glass-bonded silica, porous ceramic plastic, PVC or perforated membranes made from EPDM (ethylene propylene diene Monomer) rubber.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Air pumped through the diffuser membranes is released into the water.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] These bubbles are known as *fine bubbles*.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] The EPA defines a fine bubble as anything smaller than 2mm in diameter.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] This type of aeration has a very high oxygen transfer efficiency (OTE), sometimes as high as 15 pounds of oxygen / (horsepower * hour) (9.1 kilograms of oxygen / (kilowatt * hour)).
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] On average, diffused air aeration diffuses approximately 2–4 cfm (cubic feet of air per minute) (56.6-113.3 liters of air per minute), but some operate at levels as low as 1 cfm (28.3 L/min) or as high as 10 cfm (283 L/min).
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Fine bubble diffused aeration is able to maximize the surface area of the bubbles and thus transfer more oxygen to the water per bubble volume.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Additionally, smaller bubbles take more time to reach the surface so not only is the surface area maximized but so are the time each bubble spends in the water, allowing it more opportunity to transfer oxygen to the water.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] As a general rule, smaller bubbles and a deeper release point will generate a greater oxygen transfer rate.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] One of the drawbacks to fine bubble aeration is that the membranes of ceramic diffusers can sometimes clog and must be cleaned in order to keep them working at their optimum efficiency.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Also, they do not possess the ability to mix the water column as well as other aeration techniques, such as coarse bubble aeration.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Circulators are commonly used to mix a pond or lake and thus reduce thermal stratification.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Once circulated water reaches the surface, the air-water interface facilitates the transfer of oxygen to the lake water.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Natural resource and environmental managers have long been challenged by problems caused by thermal stratification of lakes.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Fish die-offs have been directly associated with thermal gradients, stagnation, and ice cover.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Excessive growth of plankton may limit the recreational use of lakes and the commercial use of lake water.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] With severe thermal stratification in a lake, the quality of drinking water also can be adversely affected.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] For fisheries managers, the spatial distribution of fish within a lake is often adversely affected by thermal stratification and in some cases may indirectly cause large die-offs of recreationally important fish.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] One commonly used tool to reduce the severity of these lake management problems is to eliminate or lessen thermal stratification through aeration.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Many types of aeration equipment have been used to reduce or eliminate thermal stratification.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Aeration has met with some success, although it has rarely proved to be a panacea.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] During heavy rain, London's sewage storm pipes overflow into the River Thames, sending dissolved oxygen levels plummeting and threatening the species it supports.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Two dedicated McTay Marine vessels, oxygenation barges *Thames Bubbler* and *Thames Vitality* are used to replenish oxygen levels, as part of an ongoing battle to clean up the river, which now supports 115 species of fish and hundreds more invertebrates, plants and birds.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] The dissolved oxygen concentration within Cardiff Bay in Wales are maintained at or above 5 mg/L.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Compressed air is pumped, from five sites around the Bay, through a series of steel reinforced rubber pipelines, laid on the beds of the Bay and Rivers Taff and Ely.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] These are connected to approximately 800 diffusers.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] At times this is insufficient and the Harbour Authority uses a mobile oxygenation barge built by McTay Marine with liquid oxygen stored in a tank.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Liquid oxygen is passed through an electrically heated vapouriser and the gas is injected into a stream of water which is pumped from, and returned to, the bay.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] The barge is capable of dissolving up to 5 tonnes of oxygen in 24 hours.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Similar options have been proposed to help rehabilitate the Chesapeake Bay in the US where the principal problem is lack of filter-feeding organisms such as oysters responsible for keeping the water clean.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Historically the Bay's oyster population was in the tens of billions, and they circulated the entire Bay volume in a matter of days.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Due to pollution, disease and over-harvesting their population is a fraction of historic levels.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Water that was once clear for meters is now so turbid and sediment-ridden that a wader may lose sight of their feet before their knees are wet.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Oxygen is normally supplied by submerged aquatic vegetation via photosynthesis but pollution and sediments have reduced the plant populations, resulting in a reduction of dissolved oxygen levels, rendering areas of the bay unsuitable for aerobic aquatic life.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] In a symbiotic relation the plants provide the oxygen needed for underwater organisms to proliferate, and in exchange the filter feeders keep the water clean and thus clear enough for plants to have sufficient access to sunlight.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Researchers have proposed oxygenation through artificial means as a solution to help improve water quality.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Aeration of hypoxic water-bodies seems an appealing solution and it has been tried successfully many times on freshwater ponds and small lakes.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] However no one has undertaken an aeration project as large as an estuary.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] A 353-hectare portion of the bay connected to the Rock Creek has been aerated using pipes since 2016.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] The system started as a large-bubble system intended mainly for de-stratification, creating a 74-ha oxic zone.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] It was upgraded in 2019 to fine-bubble injectors to provide more oxygen directly.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] Many water treatment processes use a variety of forms of aeration to support biological oxidative processes.
[src:algaculture/aerated-waters] A typical example is activated sludge which can use fine or coarse bubble aeration or mechanical aeration cones which draw up mixed liquor from the base of a treatment tank and eject it through the air where oxygen is entrained in the liquor.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Transmission of furunculosis mainly occurs through fish-to-fish contact by the skin or by ingestion.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Rainbow trout have been found to carry *A. salmonicida* up to two years after initial infection without re-exposure.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Chemically immunosuppressed fish compared with temperature-stressed fish had a 73% mortality as opposed to a 33% mortality rate, respectively.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Naturally occurring trout infections consisted of a 5–6% mortality rate per week with an 85% rate in untreated populations.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Some clinical furunculosis survivors of an infected trout population became *A. salmonicida* carriers.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] When comparing furunculosis epidemics with depressed oxygen levels, when oxygen concentrations were decreased to less than 5 mg/L, *A. salmonicida* concentrations increased.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] While observing chum salmon in a density of 14.7 fish per square meter, 12.4% were infected with *A. salmonicida*, whereas, densities at 4.9 fish per square meter were infection-free.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Additionally, *A. salmonicida* concentrations were considerably elevated in water with low dissolved oxygen (6–7 mg/L), compared to water with higher dissolved oxygen (10 mg/L).
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] High density-low oxygen water resulted in survival rates that were roughly 40% less than in those consisting of low density-high oxygen conditions.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] The bacterium is pathogenic for fish, and causes the disease known as furunculosis.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] The symptoms the fish show are external and internal hemorrhaging, swelling of the vents and kidneys, boils, ulcers, liquefaction, and gastroenteritis.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Furunculosis is commonly known as tail rot in fish and is common in goldfish and koi.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Infected fish with open sores are able to spread the disease to other fish.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] It is also one of several bacteria that can cause bald sea urchin disease.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Since *A. salmonicida* cannot grow at 37 °C, it is not pathogenic in humans.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Furunculosis is classified into four categories based on severity: acute, subacute, chronic, or latent.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] When fish are infected, they become listless and weak until they die.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Other characteristics observed include anorexia and lethargic movement, and they may exhibit a darkened pigment.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Deep or shallow ulcers, exophthalmia, bloody spots, distended abdomen, and petechia at the base of the fin may also occur.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Internally, the infected fish may suffer from gastroenteritis, hemorrhagic septicemia, edematous kidney, and an enlarged spleen.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] The liver may appear pale in color and the spleen may be darkened.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] The peritoneal cavity may also be bloody and inflamed.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Bacteria must be isolated to positively identify the disease.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Isolates are retrieved from muscle lesions, kidney, spleen, or liver, and then grown on trypticase soy agar and brain-heart infusion medium incubated at 20–25 °C.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Colonies of *A. salmonicida* appear hard, friable, smooth, soft, and dark in color.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] While cultural procedures produce good results, serological procedures produce more rapid results by using serum agglutination, fluorescent antibody, or enzyme linked immunosorbent assay on infected tissue or cultured bacteria.
[src:algaculture/aeromonas-salmonicida] Mooney *et al.* developed a DNA probe with polymerase chain reaction to detect *A. salmonicida* DNA; results were successful in 88% of wild Atlantic salmon.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Additionally, microorganisms are swept into the air from terrestrial dust storms, and an even larger amount of airborne marine microorganisms are propelled high into the atmosphere in sea spray.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Aeroplankton deposits hundreds of millions of airborne viruses and tens of millions of bacteria every day on every square meter around the planet.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Small, drifting aeroplankton are found everywhere in the atmosphere, reaching concentration up to 106 microbial cells per cubic metre.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Processes such as aerosolization and wind transport determine how the microorganisms are distributed in the atmosphere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Air mass circulation globally disperses vast numbers of the floating aerial organisms, which travel across and between continents, creating biogeographic patterns by surviving and settling in remote environments.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] As well as the colonization of pristine environments, the globetrotting behaviour of these organisms has human health consequences.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Airborne microorganisms are also involved in cloud formation and precipitation, and play important roles in the formation of the phyllosphere, a vast terrestrial habitat involved in nutrient cycling.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The atmosphere is the least understood biome on Earth despite its critical role as a microbial transport medium.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Recent studies have shown microorganisms are ubiquitous in the atmosphere and reach concentration up to 106 microbial cells per cubic metre (28,000/cu ft) and that they might be metabolically active.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Different processes, such as aerosolisation, might be important in selecting which microorganisms exist in the atmosphere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Another process, microbial transport in the atmosphere, is critical for understanding the role microorganisms play in meteorology, atmospheric chemistry and public health.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Changes in species geographic distributions can have strong ecological and socioeconomic consequences.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In the case of microorganisms, air mass circulation disperses vast amounts of individuals and interconnects remote environments.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Airborne microorganisms can travel between continents, survive and settle on remote environments, which creates biogeographic patterns.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The circulation of atmospheric microorganisms results in global health concerns and ecological processes such as widespread dispersal of both pathogens and antibiotic resistances, cloud formation and precipitation, and colonization of pristine environments.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Airborne microorganisms also play a role in the formation of the phyllosphere, which is one of the vastest habitats on the Earth's surface involved in nutrient cycling.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The field of bioaerosol research studies the taxonomy and community composition of airborne microbial organisms, also referred to as the air microbiome.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] A recent series of technological and analytical advancements include high-volumetric air samplers, an ultra-low biomass processing pipeline, low-input DNA sequencing libraries, as well as high-throughput sequencing technologies.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Applied in unison, these methods have enabled comprehensive and meaningful characterization of the airborne microbial organismal dynamics found in the near-surface atmosphere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Airborne microbial organisms also impact agricultural productivity, as bacterial and fungal species distributed by air movement act as plant blights.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Furthermore, atmospheric processes, such as cloud condensation and ice nucleation events were shown to depend on airborne microbial particles.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Therefore, understanding the dynamics of microbial organisms in air is crucial for insights into the atmosphere as an ecosystem, but also will inform on human wellbeing and respiratory health.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In recent years, next generation DNA sequencing technologies, such as metabarcoding as well as coordinated metagenomics and metatranscriptomics studies, have been providing new insights into microbial ecosystem functioning, and the relationships that microorganisms maintain with their environment.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] There have been studies in soils, the ocean, the human gut, and elsewhere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In the atmosphere, though, microbial gene expression and metabolic functioning remain largely unexplored, in part due to low biomass and sampling difficulties.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] So far, metagenomics has confirmed high fungal, bacterial, and viral biodiversity, and targeted genomics and transcriptomics towards ribosomal genes has supported earlier findings about the maintenance of metabolic activity in aerosols and in clouds.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In atmospheric chambers airborne bacteria have been consistently demonstrated to react to the presence of a carbon substrate by regulating ribosomal gene expressions.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Effective pollen dispersal is vital for maintenance of genetic diversity and fundamental for connectivity between spatially separated populations.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] An efficient transfer of the pollen guarantees successful reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] No matter how pollen is dispersed, the male-female recognition is possible by mutual contact of stigma and pollen surfaces.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Cytochemical reactions are responsible for pollen binding to a specific stigma.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Allergic diseases are considered to be one of the most important contemporary public health problems affecting up to 15–35% of humans worldwide.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] There is a body of evidence suggesting that allergic reactions induced by pollen are on the increase, particularly in highly industrial countries.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Fungi, a major element of atmospheric bioaerosols, are capable of existing and surviving in the air for extended periods of time.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Both the spores and the mycelium may be dangerous for people suffering from allergies, causing various health issues including asthma.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Apart from their negative impact on human health, atmospheric fungi may be dangerous for plants as sources of infection.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Moreover, fungal organisms may be capable of creating additional toxins that are harmful to humans and animals, such as endotoxins or mycotoxins.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Considering this aspect, aeromycological research is considered capable of predicting future symptoms of plant diseases in both crops and wild plants.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Fungi capable of travelling extensive distances with wind despite natural barriers, such as tall mountains, may be particularly relevant to understanding the role of fungi in plant disease.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Notably, the presence of numerous fungal organisms pathogenic to plants has been determined in mountainous regions.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] A wealth of correlative evidence suggests asthma is associated with fungi and triggered by elevated numbers of fungal spores in the environment.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Intriguing are reports of thunderstorm asthma.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In a now classic study from the United Kingdom, an outbreak of acute asthma was linked to increases in *Didymella exitialis* ascospores and *Sporobolomyces* basidiospores associated with a severe weather event.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Thunderstorms are associated with spore plumes: when spore concentrations increase dramatically over a short period of time, for example from 20,000 spores/m3 to over 170,000 spores/m3 in 2 hours.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] However, other sources consider pollen or pollution as causes of thunderstorm asthma.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Transoceanic and transcontinental dust events move large numbers of spores across vast distances and have the potential to impact public health, and similar correlative evidence links dust blown off the Sahara with pediatric emergency room admissions on the island of Trinidad.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Pteridophytes are vascular plants that disperse spores, such as fern spores.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Pteridophyte spores are similar to pollen grains and fungal spores, and are also components of aeroplankton.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Fungal spores usually rank first among bioaerosol constituents due to their count numbers which can reach to between 1,000 and 10,000 per cubic metre (28 and 283/cu ft), while pollen grains and fern spores can each reach to between 10 and 100 per cubic metre (0.28 and 2.83/cu ft).
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Many small animals, mainly arthropods (such as insects and spiders), are also carried upwards into the atmosphere by air currents and may be found floating several thousand feet up.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Aphids, for example, are frequently found at high altitudes.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Ballooning, sometimes called kiting, is a process by which spiders, and some other small invertebrates, move through the air by releasing one or more gossamer threads to catch the wind, causing them to become airborne at the mercy of air currents.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] A spider (usually limited to individuals of a small species), or spiderling after hatching, will climb as high as it can, stand on raised legs with its abdomen pointed upwards ("tiptoeing"), and then release several silk threads from its spinnerets into the air.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] These automatically form a triangular shaped parachute which carries the spider away on updrafts of winds where even the slightest of breezes will disperse the arachnid.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The flexibility of their silk draglines can aid the aerodynamics of their flight, causing the spiders to drift an unpredictable and sometimes long distance.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Even atmospheric samples collected from balloons at 5 km (3.1 mi) altitude and ships mid-ocean have reported spider landings.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Enough lift for ballooning may occur, even in windless conditions, if an electrostatic charge gradient is present in the atmosphere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Nematodes (roundworms), the most common animal taxon, are also found among aeroplankton.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Nematodes are an essential trophic link between unicellular organisms like bacteria, and larger organisms such as tardigrades, copepods, flatworms, and fishes.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] For nematodes, anhydrobiosis is a widespread strategy allowing them to survive unfavorable conditions for months and even years.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Accordingly, nematodes can be readily dispersed by wind.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] However, as reported by Vanschoenwinkel et al., nematodes account for only about one per cent of wind-drifted animals.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Among the habitats colonized by nematodes are those that are strongly exposed to wind erosion as e.g., the shorelines of permanent waters, soils, mosses, dead wood, and tree bark.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In addition, within a few days of forming temporary waters such as phytotelmata were shown to be colonized by numerous nematode species.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] A stream of unicellular airborne microorganisms circles the planet above weather systems but below commercial air lanes.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Some microorganisms are swept up from terrestrial dust storms, but most originate from marine microorganisms in sea spray.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In 2018, scientists reported that hundreds of millions of viruses and tens of millions of bacteria are deposited daily on every square meter around the planet.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The presence of airborne cyanobacteria and microalgae as well as their negative impacts on human health have been documented by many researchers worldwide.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] However, studies on cyanobacteria and microalgae are few compared with those on other bacteria and viruses.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Research is especially lacking on the presence and taxonomic composition of cyanobacteria and microalgae near economically important water bodies with much tourism.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Research on airborne algae is especially important in tourist areas near water-bodies.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Sunbathers are exposed to particularly high quantities of harmful cyanobacteria and microalgae.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Additionally, harmful microalgae and cyanobacteria blooms tend to occur in both marine and freshwater reservoirs during summer.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Previous work has shown that the Mediterranean Sea is dominated by the picocyanobacteria *Synechococcus* sp. and *Synechocystis* sp., which are responsible for the production of a group of hepatotoxins known as microcystins.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Because most tourism occurs in summer, many tourists are exposed to the most extreme negative impacts of airborne microalgae.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Airborne bacteria are emitted by most Earth surfaces (plants, oceans, land, and urban areas) to the atmosphere via a variety of mechanical processes such as aeolian soil erosion, sea spray production, or mechanical disturbances including anthropogenic activities.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Due to their relatively small size (the median aerodynamic diameter of bacteria-containing particles is around 2–4 μm), these can then be transported upward by turbulent fluxes and carried by wind to long distances.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] As a consequence, bacteria are present in the air up to at least the lower stratosphere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Given that the atmosphere is a large conveyor belt that moves air over thousands of kilometers, microorganisms are disseminated globally.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Airborne transport of microbes is therefore likely pervasive at the global scale, yet there have been only a limited number of studies that have looked at the spatial distribution of microbes across different geographical regions.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] One of the main difficulties is linked with the low microbial biomass associated with a high diversity existing in the atmosphere outdoor (~102–105 cells/m3) thus requiring reliable sampling procedures and controls.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Furthermore, the site location and its environmental specificities have to be accounted for to some extent by considering chemical and meteorological variables.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The environmental role of airborne cyanobacteria and microalgae is only partly understood.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] While present in the air, cyanobacteria and microalgae can contribute to ice nucleation and cloud droplet formation.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Cyanobacteria and microalgae can also impact human health.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Depending on their size, airborne cyanobacteria and microalgae can be inhaled by humans and settle in different parts of the respiratory system, leading to the formation or intensification of numerous diseases and ailments, e.g., allergies, dermatitis, and rhinitis.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] According to Wiśniewska et al., these harmful microorganisms can constitute between 13% and 71% of sampled taxa.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] However, the interplay between microbes and atmospheric physical and chemical conditions is an open field of research that can only be fully addressed using multidisciplinary approaches.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Airborne microalgae and cyanobacteria are the most poorly studied organisms in aerobiology and phycology.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] This lack of knowledge may result from the lack of standard methods for both sampling and further analysis, especially quantitative analytical methods.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Few studies have been performed to determine the number of cyanobacteria and microalgae in the atmosphere However, it was shown in 2012 that the average quantity of atmospheric algae is between 100 and 1000 cells per cubic meter of air.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] As of 2019, about 350 taxa of cyanobacteria and microalgae have been documented in the atmosphere worldwide.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Cyanobacteria and microalgae end up in the air as a consequence of their emission from soil, buildings, trees, and roofs.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The bacterium *Pseudomonas syringae* can manufacture ice nucleation active (INA) proteins (which cause water in plants to freeze at temperatures higher than normal freezing point).
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In airborne versions of *P. syringae*, these proteins serve as atmospheric biological ice nucleators, so the bacteria can function as cloud condensation nuclei.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Recent evidence has suggested the species plays a larger role than previously thought in producing rain and snow.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] They have also been found in the cores of hailstones, aiding in bioprecipitation.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Biological particles are known to represent a significant fraction (~20–70%) of the total number of aerosols > 0.2 μm, with large spatial and temporal variations.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Among these, microorganisms are of particular interest in fields as diverse as epidemiology, including phytopathology, bioterrorism, forensic science, and public health, and environmental sciences, like microbial ecology, meteorology and climatology.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] More precisely concerning the latter, airborne microorganisms contribute to the pool of particles nucleating the condensation and crystallization of water and they are thus potentially involved in cloud formation and in the triggering of precipitation.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Additionally, viable microbial cells act as chemical catalyzers interfering with atmospheric chemistry.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The constant flux of bacteria from the atmosphere to the Earth's surface due to precipitation and dry deposition can also affect global biodiversity, but they are rarely taken into account when conducting ecological surveys.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] As stressed by these studies attempting to decipher and understand the spread of microbes over the planet, concerted data are needed for documenting the abundance and distribution of airborne microorganisms, including at remote and altitudes sites.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Bioaerosols, known also as primary biological aerosols, are the subset of atmospheric particles that are directly released from the biosphere into the atmosphere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] They include living and dead organisms (e.g., algae, archaea, bacteria ), dispersal units (e.g., fungal spores and plant pollen ), and various fragments or excretions (e.g., plant debris and brochosomes).
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Bioaerosol particle diameters range from nanometers up to about a tenth of a millimeter.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The upper limit of the aerosol particle size range is determined by rapid sedimentation, i.e., larger particles are too heavy to remain airborne for extended periods of time.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Bioaerosols include living and dead organisms as well as their fragments and excrements emitted from the biosphere into the atmosphere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Included are archaea, fungi, microalgae, cyanobacteria, bacteria, viruses, plant cell debris, and pollen.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Historically, the first investigations of the occurrence and dispersion of microorganisms and spores in the air can be traced back to the early 19th century.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Bioaerosols play a key role in the dispersal of reproductive units from plants and microbes (pollen, spores, etc.), for which the atmosphere enables transport over geographic barriers and long distances.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Bioaerosols are thus highly relevant for the spread of organisms, allowing genetic exchange between habitats and geographic shifts of biomes.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] They are central elements in the development, evolution, and dynamics of ecosystems.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Dispersal is a vital component of an organism's life-history, and the potential for dispersal determines the distribution, abundance, and thus, the community dynamics of species at different sites.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] A new habitat must first be reached before filters such as organismal abilities and adaptations, the quality of a habitat, and the established biological community determine the colonization efficiency of a species.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] While larger animals can cover distances on their own and actively seek suitable habitats, small (<2 mm) organisms are often passively dispersed, resulting in their more ubiquitous occurrence.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] While active dispersal accounts for rather predictable distribution patterns, passive dispersal leads to a more randomized immigration of organisms.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Mechanisms for passive dispersal are the transport on (epizoochory) or in (endozoochory) larger animals (e.g., flying insects, birds, or mammals) and the erosion by wind.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] A propagule is any material that functions in propagating an organism to the next stage in its life cycle, such as by dispersal.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The propagule is usually distinct in form from the parent organism.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Propagules are produced by plants (in the form of seeds or spores), fungi (in the form of spores), and bacteria (for example endospores or microbial cysts).
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Often cited as an important requirement for effective wind dispersal is the presence of propagules (e.g., resting eggs, cysts, ephippia, juvenile and adult resting stages), which also enables organisms to survive unfavorable environmental conditions until they enter a suitable habitat.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] These dispersal units can be blown from surfaces such as soil, moss, and the desiccated sediments of temporary or intermittent waters.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The passively dispersed organisms are typically pioneer colonizers.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] However, wind-drifted species vary in their vagility (probability to be transported with the wind), with the weight and form of the propagules, and therefore, the wind speed required for their transport, determining the dispersal distance.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] For example, in nematodes, resting eggs are less effectively transported by wind than other life stages, while organisms in anhydrobiosis are lighter and thus more readily transported than hydrated forms.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Because different organisms are, for the most part, not dispersed over the same distances, source habitats are also important, with the number of organisms contained in air declining with increasing distance from the source system.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The distances covered by small animals range from a few meters, to hundreds, to thousands of meters.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] While the wind dispersal of aquatic organisms is possible even during the wet phase of a transiently aquatic habitat, during the dry stages a larger number of dormant propagules are exposed to wind and thus dispersed.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Freshwater organisms that must "cross the dry ocean" to enter new aquatic island systems will be passively dispersed more successfully than terrestrial taxa.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Numerous taxa from both soil and freshwater systems have been captured from the air (e.g., bacteria, several algae, ciliates, flagellates, rotifers, crustaceans, mites, and tardigrades).
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] While these have been qualitatively well studied, accurate estimates of their dispersal rates are lacking.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Once aerosolized, microbial cells enter the planetary boundary layer, defined as the air layer near the ground directly influenced by the planetary surface.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The concentration and taxonomic diversity of airborne microbial communities in the planetary boundary layer has been recently described, though the functional potential of airborne microbial communities remains unknown.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] From the planetary boundary layer, the microbial community might eventually be transported upwards by air currents into the free troposphere (air layer above the planetary boundary layer) or even higher into the stratosphere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Microorganisms might undergo a selection process during their way up into the troposphere and the stratosphere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Subject to gravity, aerosols (or particulate matter) as well as bioaerosols become concentrated in the lower part of the troposphere that is called the planetary boundary layer.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The various atmospheric phases represent multiple biological niches.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Possible processes in the way atmospheric microbial communities can distribute themselves have recently been investigated in meteorology, seasons, surface conditions and global air circulation.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Microorganisms attached to aerosols can travel intercontinental distances, survive, and further colonize remote environments.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Airborne microbes are influenced by environmental and climatic patterns that are predicted to change in the near future, with unknown consequences.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Airborne microbial communities play significant roles in public health and meteorological processes, so it is important to understand how these communities are distributed over time and space.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Most studies have focused on laboratory cultivation to identify possible metabolic functions of microbial strains of atmospheric origin, mainly from cloud water.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] There are some metagenomic studies on airborne microbial communities over specific sites.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] This observed correlation of microbial-community functional potential and the physical and chemical characteristics of their environments could have resulted from genetic modifications (microbial adaptation ) and/or physical selection.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The latter refers to the death of sensitive cells and the survival of resistant or previously adapted cells.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] This physical selection can occur when microorganisms are exposed to physiologically adverse conditions.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The presence of a specific microbial functional signature in the atmosphere has not been investigated yet.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Microbial strains of airborne origin have been shown to survive and develop under conditions typically found in cloud water (i.e., high concentrations of H2O2, typical cloud carbonaceous sources, ultraviolet – UV – radiation etc.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] While atmospheric chemicals might lead to some microbial adaptation, physical and unfavorable conditions of the atmosphere such as UV radiation, low water content and cold temperatures might select which microorganisms can survive in the atmosphere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] From the pool of microbial cells being aerosolized from Earth's surfaces, these adverse conditions might act as a filter in selecting cells already resistant to unfavorable physical conditions.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Fungal cells and especially fungal spores might be particularly adapted to survive in the atmosphere due to their innate resistance and might behave differently than bacterial cells.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Still, the proportion and nature (i.e., fungi versus bacteria) of microbial cells that are resistant to the harsh atmospheric conditions within airborne microbial communities are unknown.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Airborne microbial transport is central to dispersal outcomes and several studies have demonstrated diverse microbial biosignatures are recoverable from the atmosphere.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Microbial transport has been shown to occur across inter-continental distances above terrestrial habitats.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Variation has been recorded seasonally, with underlying land use, and due to stochastic weather events such as dust storms.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] There is evidence specific bacterial taxa (e.g., Actinomycetota and some Gammaproteobacteria) are preferentially aerosolized from oceans.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] As a result of rapid industrialization and urbanization, global megacities have been impacted by extensive and intense particulate matter pollution events, which have potential human health consequences.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Severe particulate matter pollution is associated with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease and asthma, as well as risks for early death.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] While the chemical components of particulate matter pollution and their impacts on human health have been widely studied, the potential impact of pollutant-associated microbes remains unclear.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Airborne microbial exposure, including exposure to dust-associated organisms, has been established to both protect against and exacerbate certain diseases.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Understanding the temporal dynamics of the taxonomic and functional diversity of microorganisms in urban air, especially during smog events, will improve understanding of the potential microbe-associated health consequences.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Recent advances in airborne particle DNA extraction and metagenomic library preparation have enabled low biomass environments to be subject to shotgun sequencing analysis.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In 2020, Qin *et al.* used shotgun sequencing analysis to reveal a great diversity of microbial species and antibiotic resistant genes in Beijing's particulate matter, largely consistent with a recent study.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The data suggest that potential pathogen and antibiotic resistance burden increases with increasing pollution levels and that severe smog events promote the exposure.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In addition, the particulate matter also contained several bacteria that harbored antibiotic resistant genes flanked by mobile genetic elements, which could be associated with horizontal gene transfer.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Many of these bacteria were typical or putative members of the human microbiome.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The outdoor atmosphere harbors diverse microbial assemblages composed of bacteria, fungi and viruses whose functioning remains largely unexplored.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] While the occasional presence of human pathogens or opportunists can cause potential hazard, in general the vast majority of airborne microbes originate from natural environments like soil or plants, with large spatial and temporal variations of biomass and biodiversity.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Once ripped off and aerosolized from surfaces by mechanical disturbances such as those generated by wind, raindrop impacts or water bubbling, microbial cells are transported upward by turbulent fluxes.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Living airborne microorganisms may end up concretizing aerial dispersion by colonizing their new habitat, provided that they survive their journey from emission to deposition.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Bacterial survival is indeed naturally impaired during atmospheric transport, but a fraction remains viable.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] At high altitude, the peculiar environments offered by cloud droplets are thus regarded in some aspects as temporary microbial habitats, providing water and nutrients to airborne living cells.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In addition, the detection of low levels of heterotrophy raises questions about microbial functioning in cloud water and its potential influence on the chemical reactivity of these complex and dynamic environments.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] The metabolic functioning of microbial cells in clouds is still albeit unknown, while fundamental for apprehending microbial life conditions during long distance aerial transport and their geochemical and ecological impacts.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Aerosols affect cloud formation, thereby influencing sunlight irradiation and precipitation, but the extent to which and the manner in which they influence climate remains uncertain.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Marine aerosols consist of a complex mixture of sea salt, non-sea-salt sulfate and organic molecules and can function as nuclei for cloud condensation, influencing the radiation balance and, hence, climate.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] For example, biogenic aerosols in remote marine environments (for example, the Southern Ocean) can increase the number and size of cloud droplets, having similar effects on climate as aerosols in highly polluted regions.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Specifically, phytoplankton emit dimethylsulfide, and its derivate sulfate promotes cloud condensation.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Understanding the ways in which marine phytoplankton contribute to aerosols will allow better predictions of how changing ocean conditions will affect clouds and feed back on climate.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In addition, the atmosphere itself contains about 1022 microbial cells, and determining the ability of atmospheric microorganisms to grow and form aggregates will be valuable for assessing their influence on climate.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] They have formulated the hypothesis of the microbial formation of phosphine, envisaging the possibility of a liveable window in the Venusian clouds at a certain altitude with an acceptable temperature range for microbial life.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] However, in 2021 Hallsworth *et al.* examined the conditions required to support the life of extremophile microorganisms in the clouds at high altitude in the Venusian atmosphere where favorable temperature conditions might prevail.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Beside the presence of sulfuric acid in the clouds which already represent a major challenge for the survival of most of microorganisms, they came to the conclusion that the Venusian atmosphere is too dry to host microbial life.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] They determined a water activity ≤ 0.004, two orders of magnitude below the 0.585 limit for known extremophiles.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] While the physical and chemical properties of airborne particulate matter have been extensively studied, their associated airborne microbiome remains largely unexplored.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Microbiomes are defined as characteristic microbial communities, which include prokaryotes, fungi, protozoa, other micro-eukaryotes and viruses, that occupy well-defined habitats.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Throughout Earth's history, microbial communities have changed the climate, and climate has shaped microbial communities.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Microorganisms can modify ecosystem processes or biogeochemistry on a global scale, and we start to uncover their role and potential involvement in changing the climate.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] However, the effects of climate change on microbial communities (i.e., diversity, dynamics, or distribution) are rarely addressed.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In the case of fungal aerobiota, its composition is likely influenced by dispersal ability, rather than season or climate.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Indeed, the origin of air masses from marine, terrestrial, or anthropogenic-impacted environments, mainly shapes the atmospheric air microbiome.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] However, recent studies have shown that meteorological factors and seasonality influence the composition of airborne bacterial communities.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] This evidence suggests that climatic conditions may act as an environmental filter for the aeroplankton, selecting a subset of species from the regional pool, and raises the question of the relative importance of the different factors affecting both bacterial and eukaryal aeroplankton.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In 2020, Archer *et al.* reported evidence for a dynamic microbial presence at the ocean–atmosphere interface at the Great Barrier Reef, and identified air mass trajectories over oceanic and continental surfaces associated with observed shifts in airborne bacterial and fungal diversity.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Relative abundance of shared taxa between air and coral microbiomes varied between 2.2 and 8.8% and included those identified as part of the core coral microbiome.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Above marine systems, the abundance of microorganisms decreases exponentially with distance from land, but relatively little is known about potential patterns in biodiversity for airborne microorganisms above the oceans.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] Here we test the hypothesis that persistent microbial inputs to the ocean–atmosphere interface of the Great Barrier Reef ecosystem vary according to surface cover (i.e. land vs. ocean) during transit of the air-mass.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In 2021, researchers demonstrated that environmental DNA (eDNA) can be collected from air and used to identify mammals.
[src:algaculture/aeroplankton] In 2023, scientists developed a specialized sampling probe and aircraft surveys to assess biodiversity of multiple taxa, including mammals, using air eDNA.
[src:algaculture/agar] As found in nature, agar is a mixture of two components, the linear polysaccharide agarose and a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules called agaropectin.
[src:algaculture/agar] It forms the supporting structure in the cell walls of certain species of algae, and is released on boiling.
[src:algaculture/agar] The processing of food-grade agar removes the agaropectin, and the commercial product is essentially pure agarose.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar has been used as an ingredient in desserts throughout Asia and also as a solid substrate to contain culture media for microbiological work.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar can be used as a laxative; an appetite suppressant; a vegan substitute for gelatin; a thickener for soups; in fruit preserves, ice cream, and other desserts; as a clarifying agent in brewing; and for sizing paper and fabrics.
[src:algaculture/agar] The word *agar* comes from **agar-agar**, the Malay name for red algae (*Gigartina*, *Eucheuma*, *Gracilaria*) from which the jelly is produced.
[src:algaculture/agar] It is also known as **kanten** (Japanese: 寒天) (from the phrase ***kan**-zarashi tokoro**ten*** (寒晒し心太) or "cold-exposed agar"), **Japanese isinglass**, **China grass**, **Ceylon moss**, and **Jaffna moss**.
[src:algaculture/agar] *Gracilaria edulis* or its synonym *G. lichenoides* is specifically referred to as **agal-agal** or **Ceylon agar**.
[src:algaculture/agar] Macroalgae have been used widely as food by coastal cultures, especially in Southeast Asia.
[src:algaculture/agar] In the Philippines, *Gracilaria*, known as *gulaman* (also *guraman*, *gar-garao*, or *gulaman dagat*, among other names) in Tagalog, have been harvested and used as food for centuries, eaten both fresh or sun-dried and turned into jellies.
[src:algaculture/agar] Carrageenan, derived from gusô (*Eucheuma* spp.), which also congeals into a gel-like texture is also used similarly among the Visayan peoples and have been recorded in the even earlier *Diccionario De La Lengua Bisaya, Hiligueina y Haraia de la isla de Panay y Sugbu y para las demas islas* (c.
[src:algaculture/agar] 1637) of the Augustinian missionary Alonso de Méntrida (in Spanish).
[src:algaculture/agar] In the book, Méntrida describes gusô as being cooked until it melts, and then allowed to congeal into a sour dish.
[src:algaculture/agar] In Ambon Island in the Maluku Islands of Indonesia, agar is extracted from *Graciliaria* and eaten as a type of pickle or a sauce.
[src:algaculture/agar] Jelly seaweeds were also favoured and foraged by Malay communities living on the coasts of the Riau Archipelago and Singapore in Southeast Asia for centuries.
[src:algaculture/agar] 19th century records indicate that dried *Graciliaria* were one of the bulk exports of British Malaya to China.
[src:algaculture/agar] Poultices made from agar were also used for swollen knee joints and sores in Johore and Singapore.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar normally solidifies at room temperature without the need to freeze.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar was first subjected to chemical analysis in 1859 by the French chemist Anselme Payen, who had obtained agar from the marine algae *Gelidium corneum*.
[src:algaculture/agar] Beginning in the late 19th century, agar began to be used as a solid medium for growing various microbes.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar was first described for use in microbiology in 1882 by the German microbiologist Walther Hesse, an assistant working in Robert Koch's laboratory, on the suggestion of his wife Fanny Hesse.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar quickly supplanted gelatin as the base of microbiological media, due to its higher melting temperature, allowing microbes to be grown at higher temperatures without the media liquefying.
[src:algaculture/agar] With its newfound use in microbiology, agar production quickly increased.
[src:algaculture/agar] This production centered on Japan, which produced most of the world's agar until World War II.
[src:algaculture/agar] However, with the outbreak of World War II, many nations were forced to establish domestic agar industries in order to continue microbiological research.
[src:algaculture/agar] Around the time of World War II, approximately 2,500 tons of agar were produced annually.
[src:algaculture/agar] By the mid-1970s, production worldwide had increased dramatically to approximately 10,000 tons each year.
[src:algaculture/agar] Since then, production of agar has fluctuated due to unstable and sometimes over-utilized seaweed populations.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar consists of a mixture of two polysaccharides: agarose and agaropectin.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agarose constitutes about 70% of the mixture, while agaropectin constitutes about 30% of it.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agarose is a linear polymer made up of repeating units of agarobiose, a disaccharide made up of D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-L-galactopyranose.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agaropectin is a heterogeneous mixture of smaller molecules that occur in lesser amounts, and is made up of alternating units of D-galactose and L-galactose heavily modified with acidic side-groups, such as sulfate, glucuronate, and pyruvate.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar exhibits a phenomenon known as hysteresis whereby, when mixed with water, it solidifies and forms a gel below about 32–42 °C (305–315 K; 90–108 °F), which is called the gel point, and melts above 85 °C (358 K; 185 °F), which is the melting point.
[src:algaculture/agar] Hysteresis is the property of having a difference between the gel point and melting point temperatures.
[src:algaculture/agar] This property lends a suitable balance between easy melting and good gel stability at relatively high temperatures.
[src:algaculture/agar] Since many scientific applications require incubation at temperatures close to human body temperature (37 °C), agar is more appropriate than other solidifying agents that melt at this temperature, such as gelatin.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar-agar is a natural vegetable gelatin counterpart.
[src:algaculture/agar] It is white and semi-translucent when sold in packages as washed and dried strips or in powdered form.
[src:algaculture/agar] It can be used to make jellies, puddings, and custards.
[src:algaculture/agar] When making jelly, it is boiled in water until the solids dissolve.
[src:algaculture/agar] Sweetener, flavoring, coloring, fruits and or vegetables are then added, and the liquid is poured into molds to be served as desserts and vegetable aspics or incorporated with other desserts such as a layer of jelly in a cake.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar-agar is approximately 80% dietary fiber, so it can serve as an intestinal regulator.
[src:algaculture/agar] Its bulking quality has been behind fad diets in Asia, for example the *kanten* (the Japanese word for agar-agar) diet.
[src:algaculture/agar] Once ingested, *kanten* triples in size and absorbs water.
[src:algaculture/agar] This results in the consumers feeling fuller.
[src:algaculture/agar] One use of agar in Japanese cuisine is in *anmitsu*, a dessert made of small cubes of agar jelly and served in a bowl with various fruits or other ingredients.
[src:algaculture/agar] It is also the main ingredient in *mizu yōkan*, another popular Japanese food.
[src:algaculture/agar] In Philippine cuisine, it is used to make the jelly bars in the various gulaman refreshments like *sago't gulaman*, *samalamig*, or desserts such as *buko pandan*, *agar flan*, *halo-halo*, *fruit cocktail jelly*, and the black and red *gulaman* used in various fruit salads.
[src:algaculture/agar] In Vietnamese cuisine, jellies made of flavored layers of agar-agar, called *thạch*, are a popular dessert, and are often made in ornate molds for special occasions.
[src:algaculture/agar] In Indian cuisine, agar is used for making desserts.
[src:algaculture/agar] In Burmese cuisine, a sweet jelly known as *kyauk kyaw* is made from agar.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar jelly is widely used in Taiwanese bubble tea.
[src:algaculture/agar] It can be used as addition to (or as a replacement for) pectin in jelly, jam, or marmalade, as a substitute to gelatin for its superior gelling properties, and as a strengthening ingredient in souffles and custards.
[src:algaculture/agar] Another use of agar-agar is in a Russian dish *ptich'ye moloko* (bird's milk), a rich jellified custard (or soft meringue) used as a cake filling or chocolate-glazed as individual sweets.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar-agar may also be used as the gelling agent in gel clarification, a culinary technique used to clarify stocks, sauces, and other liquids.
[src:algaculture/agar] Mexico has traditional candies made out of Agar gelatin, most of them in colorful, half-circle shapes that resemble a melon or watermelon fruit slice, and commonly covered with sugar.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar-agar is an allowed nonorganic/nonsynthetic additive used as a thickener, gelling agent, texturizer, moisturizer, emulsifier, flavor enhancer, and absorbent in certified organic foods.
[src:algaculture/agar] An agar plate or Petri dish is used to provide a growth medium using a mix of agar and other nutrients in which microorganisms, including bacteria and fungi, can be cultured and observed under the microscope.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar is indigestible for many organisms so that microbial growth does not affect the gel used and it remains stable.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar is typically sold commercially as a powder that can be mixed with water and prepared similarly to gelatin before use as a growth medium.
[src:algaculture/agar] Nutrients are typically added to meet the nutritional needs of the microbes organism, the formulations of which may be "undefined" where the precise composition is unknown, or "defined" where the exact chemical composition is known.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar is often dispensed using a sterile media dispenser.
[src:algaculture/agar] Different algae produce various types of agar.
[src:algaculture/agar] Each agar has unique properties that suit different purposes.
[src:algaculture/agar] Because of the agarose component, the agar solidifies.
[src:algaculture/agar] When heated, agarose has the potential to melt and then solidify.
[src:algaculture/agar] Because of this property, they are referred to as "physical gels".
[src:algaculture/agar] In contrast, polyacrylamide polymerization is an irreversible process, and the resulting products are known as chemical gels.
[src:algaculture/agar] There are a variety of different types of agar that support the growth of different microorganisms.
[src:algaculture/agar] A nutrient agar may be permissive, allowing for the cultivation of any non-fastidious microorganisms; a commonly used nutrient agar for bacteria is the Luria Bertani (LB) agar which contains lysogeny broth, a nutrient-rich medium used for bacterial growth.
[src:algaculture/agar] Additionally, 2216 Marine Broth (MB) agar, with high salt content, is optimized for growing heterotrophic marine bacteria like those of the *Vibrio* genus, while Terrific Broth (TB) agar is used to non-selectively culture high yields of the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:algaculture/agar] More generally, enriched media is an agar variety that is infused with the necessary nutrients required by fastidious organisms to grow.
[src:algaculture/agar] Despite the large diversity of agar mediums, yeast extract is a common ingredient across all varieties as it is a macronutrient that provides a nitrogen source for all bacterial cell types.
[src:algaculture/agar] Other fastidious organisms may require the addition of different biological fluids such as horse or sheep blood, serum, egg yolk, and so on.
[src:algaculture/agar] Agar plates can also be selective, and can be used to promote the growth of bacteria of interest while inhibiting others.
[src:algaculture/agar] A variety of chemicals may be added to create an environment favourable for specific types of bacteria or bacteria with certain properties, but not conducive for growth of others.
[src:algaculture/agar] For example, antibiotics may be added in cloning experiments whereby bacteria with antibiotic-resistant plasmid are selected.
[src:algaculture/agar] In addition to antibiotic treated agar, other selective and indicator agar plates include TCBS agar and MacConkey agar.
[src:algaculture/agar] Thiosulfate citrate bile salts sucrose (TCBS) agar is used to differentiate Vibrio species based on their sucrose metabolism, since only some will metabolize the sucrose in the plate and change its pH.
[src:algaculture/agar] Indicator dyes included in the gel will display a visual change of the pH by changing the gel color from green to yellow.
[src:algaculture/agar] MacConkey agar contains bile salts and crystal violet to selectively grow gram-negative bacteria and differentiate between species using pH-indicator dyes that demonstrate lactose metabolism properties.
[src:algaculture/agar] As a gel, an agar or agarose medium is porous and therefore can be used to measure microorganism motility and mobility.
[src:algaculture/agar] The gel's porosity is directly related to the concentration of agarose in the medium, so various levels of effective viscosity (from the cell's "point of view") can be selected, depending on the experimental objectives.
[src:algaculture/agar] A common identification assay involves culturing a sample of the organism deep within a block of nutrient agar.
[src:algaculture/agar] Cells will attempt to grow within the gel structure.
[src:algaculture/agar] Motile species will be able to migrate, albeit slowly, throughout the gel, and infiltration rates can then be visualized, whereas non-motile species will show growth only along the now-empty path introduced by the invasive initial sample deposition.
[src:algaculture/agar] Another setup commonly used for measuring chemotaxis and chemokinesis utilizes the under-agarose cell migration assay, whereby a layer of agarose gel is placed between a cell population and a chemoattractant.
[src:algaculture/agar] As a concentration gradient develops from the diffusion of the chemoattractant into the gel, various cell populations requiring different stimulation levels to migrate can then be visualized over time using microphotography as they tunnel upward through the gel against gravity along the gradient.
[src:algaculture/agar] Research grade agar is used extensively in plant biology as it is optionally supplemented with a nutrient and/or vitamin mixture that allows for seedling germination in Petri dishes under sterile conditions (given that the seeds are sterilized as well).
[src:algaculture/agar] Nutrient and/or vitamin supplementation for *Arabidopsis thaliana* is standard across most experimental conditions.
[src:algaculture/agar] Murashige & Skoog (MS) nutrient mix and Gamborg's B5 vitamin mix in general are used.
[src:algaculture/agar] A 1.0% agar/0.44% MS+vitamin dH2O solution is suitable for growth media between normal growth temps.
[src:algaculture/agar] When using agar, within any growth medium, it is important to know that the solidification of the agar is pH-dependent.
[src:algaculture/agar] The optimal range for solidification is between 5.4 and 5.7.
[src:algaculture/agar] Usually, the application of potassium hydroxide is needed to increase the pH to this range.
[src:algaculture/agar] A general guideline is about 600 μl 0.1M KOH per 250 ml GM.
[src:algaculture/agar] This entire mixture can be sterilized using the liquid cycle of an autoclave.
[src:algaculture/agar] This hormone/GM solution can be spread across the surface of Petri dishes sown with germinated and/or etiolated seedlings.
[src:algaculture/agar] Experiments with the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, however, have shown that choice of the gelling agent – agar or Gelrite – does influence phytohormone sensitivity of the plant cell culture.
[src:algaculture/agar] Gelidium agar is used primarily for bacteriological plates.
[src:algaculture/agar] Gracilaria agar is used mainly in food applications.
[src:algaculture/agar] In 2016, AMAM, a Japanese company, developed a prototype for agar-based commercial packaging system called Agar Plasticity, intended as a replacement for oil-based plastic packaging.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The **Agulhas Bank** (/əˈɡʌləs/, from Portuguese for Cape Agulhas, *Cabo das Agulhas*, "Cape of Needles") is a broad, shallow part of the southern African continental shelf which extends up to 250 km (160 mi) south of Cape Agulhas before falling steeply to the abyssal plain.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] It is the ocean region where the warm Indian Ocean and the cold Atlantic Ocean meet.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] This convergence leads to treacherous sailing conditions, accounting for numerous wrecked ships in the area over the years.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] However, the meeting of the oceans here also fuels the nutrient cycle for marine life, making it one of the best fishing grounds in South Africa.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Agulhas Bank stretches approximately 800 km (500 mi) along the African coast, from off Cape Peninsula (18°E) to Port Alfred (26°E), and up to 250 km (160 mi) from it.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The bank slopes down relatively steeply from the coast to about 50 m (160 ft) deep and reaches 200 m (660 ft) before dropping very steeply to 1,000 m (3,300 ft) on its southern edge.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The shelf spans an area of 116,000 km2 (45,000 sq mi) with a mean depth slightly over 100 m (330 ft).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] It is entirely within the exclusive economic zone of South Africa.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The National Spatial Biodiversity Assessment 2004 recognised 34 biozones nested within 9 bioregions (of which four were offshore).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The National Biodiversity Assessment of 2011 replaced these ecozones and biozones with the terms ecoregions and ecozones.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] In 2011, the Agulhas Ecoregion was divided into four distinct ecozones: Agulhas inshore, Agulhas inner shelf, Agulhas outer shelf, and Agulhas shelf edge.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] 33 different benthic habitats types were identified on the Agulhas Bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Dozens of warm temperate reefs along the coast of the Agulhas Ecoregion span from 5–30 m (16–98 ft) below sea level.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Many rocky sub-tidal reefs are of aeolianite or sandstone origin, but granite, quartzite and siltstone reefs are also present.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Agulhas reefs are heterogeneous and include several possible different sub-types.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Some of these reefs are within protected areas, but only a few areas included prohibit fishing.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Agulhas Bank is a natural boundary between ocean currents from the Atlantic Ocean, Indian Ocean, and Southern Ocean, resulting in some of the most turbulent waters found in the world's oceans.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Agulhas Current flows south along the eastern African coast and along the south-eastern edge of the bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] It then retroflects back into the Indian Ocean south-west of the bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] This retroflection results in intense eddy activities such as meanders, eddies, and filaments.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] In the upper watercolumn, the eponymous "Agulhas rings" or "Agulhas eddies" move warm and salty water into the large South Atlantic gyre, ultimately exporting it to the tropics; while in lower ocean layers water is transported in the opposite direction.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Cyclonic eddies are another source of edge upwelling, notably occurring to the west of Port Elisabeth.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Plumes of warm surface water migrate onto the bank along its eastern edge, providing subtropical surface water from the Indian Ocean to the region.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] In summer, easterly winds can intermittently drive coastal upwelling along the southern South African coast.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Agulhas Bank region is dominated by westerly winds, and most of the upwelling on the bank is therefore related to the interactions of the Agulhas Current on its eastern edge, but easterly winds do occur (especially in summer and fall) and can generate local upwelling cells.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] As the current is diverted away from the coast, dynamic processes draw an Ekman layer of cooler water up shoreward from below the warmer shelf-edge flow.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] In spring and summer, at a depth of 100 m (330 ft), a semi-permanent ridge of cold water is present on the eastern and central shelf.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] In summer months, a mixture of subtropical water separated by thermoclines from cool waters forms, though with considerable seasonal variation.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] On the shelf, deeper waters exhibit characteristics of the central Indian Ocean in the east, and central Atlantic Ocean waters in the west.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] As the Agulhas Current flows south along the African east coast, it is frequently diverted inshore, a deviation from the current's normal path known as Agulhas Current meanders (ACM).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] These bulges are occasionally (1-7 times per year) followed by a much larger offshore bulge, known as Natal pulses (NP).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Natal pulses move along the coast at 20 km (12 mi) per day.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] An ACM can bulge up to 20 km (12 mi) and a NP up to 120 km (75 mi) from the current's mean position.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The AC passes 34 km (21 mi) offshore and an ACM can reach 123 km (76 mi) offshore.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] When the AC meanders, its width broadens from 88 km (55 mi) to 125 km (78 mi) and its velocity decreases from 208 cm/s (82 in/s) to 136 cm/s (54 in/s).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] An ACM induces a strong inshore counter-current.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Large-scale cyclonic meanders from Natal pulses are formed as the Agulhas Current reaches the continental shelf on the eastern South African coast (i.e. the eastern Agulhas Bank off Natal).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] As these pulses move along the Agulhas Bank, they tend to pinch off Agulhas rings.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Such ring shedding can be triggered by a Natal pulse alone, but meanders on the Agulhas Return Current may merge to contribute to Agulhas ring formation.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Agulhas rings are large anticyclonic eddies or warm core rings of ocean water that are pinched off the Agulhas Current along the eastern edge of the Agulhas Bank from where they move into the South Atlantic.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] As the Agulhas Current reaches the east coast of South Africa, large solitary meanders known as Natal pulses form at irregular intervals.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] 165 days after the appearance of a Natal pulse, an Agulhas ring will form off Durban.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Agulhas rings are among the largest eddies in the world and play an important role in the Agulhas Leakage, the transport of warm water from the Indian Ocean to the Atlantic Ocean, affecting global climate.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The average diameter of these Agulhas rings is of 320 km (200 mi), but they can grow to over 500 km.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] They extend down to the ocean floor, circulating at 0.3–1.5 m/s (0.98–4.92 ft/s), and move into the South Atlantic at 4–8 km (2.5–5.0 mi)/day.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Only half of the Agulhas eddies that leave the Cape Basin manage to cross the Walvis Ridge, and those that do tend to lose half their energy within the six months before reaching the ridge.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Agulhas rings transport an estimated 1-5 Sv (millions m2/s) of water from the Indian Ocean to the South Atlantic.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Agulhas rings are thought to be of global climatic importance.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Cold, cyclonic eddies have been observed in the south-western Atlantic.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Based on model simulations, researchers have found that the interaction of the Agulhas Current and the eastern edge of the bank are responsible for Agulhas rings.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The provenance of ocean sediments can be determined by analysing terrigenous strontium isotope ratios in deep ocean core samples.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Sediments underlying the Agulhas Current and Return Current have significantly differing ratios to those of surrounding sediments.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Analyses of cores in the South Atlantic deposited during the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM, 20 000 years ago), show that the Agulhas leakage (shedding of Agulhas rings) was significantly reduced during the period.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] It has been hypothesised that the reason for this was a relatively stronger Agulhas Current, resulting in more eastward retroflection (and therefore less leakage).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] However, analyses of such cores south of the African coast show that the trajectory of the current was the same during the LGM, and that the reduced leakage must be explained by a weaker current.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Consequently, it can be predicted that a stronger Agulhas Current will result in its retroflection occurring more eastward, with an increased Agulhas leakage.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Compared to the Agulhas Current, the Benguela Current on the west and south-west coast of Africa is more intense and steadier.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Its dynamic southern upwelling system is driven by the prevailing northward winds that produce an intense off-shore Ekman transport.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Most of this upwelling is concentrated to a few upwelling cells in the southern region: Namaqua (30°S), Cape Columbine (32.5°S), and Cape Peninsula (34°S).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The wind is most intense from October to February, and the contrast in sea surface temperature between the open sea and the shelf is most prominent during summer.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Coastal upwelling is also common on the western bank, but the more stable atmospheric condition results in larger cold water plumes that sometimes merge to form a continuous upwelling regime along the South African south-west coast.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] This upwelling zone is the southernmost extension of the Benguela Current Large Maritime Ecosystem.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Agulhas Current regularly flows around the southern tip of the bank and brings warm water to the western bank along the bank's western edge.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Regularly, the mesoscale eddies from the east interact with the Benguela upwelling system on the African west coast.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Flowing south along the South American continental slope, the Deep Western Boundary Current (DWBC) carries North Atlantic Deep Water (NADW) into the South Atlantic.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] At about 8°S and at a depth of 2,200–3,500 m (7,200–11,500 ft), the DWBC breaks into anticyclonic eddies during periods of strong meridional overturning circulation.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] One such NADW eddy was observed in 2003 and the researchers speculated that a deeply penetrating Agulhas ring pinched it off the NADW slope current.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Spinning at 20 cm/s (7.9 in/s), these deep-water eddies move around the southern tip of the Agulhas Bank and into the Indian Ocean.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Most of the NADW flow (more than 7 Sv) meanders east around the Agulhas Plateau together with the surface Agulhas Return Current, but a smaller portion (3 Sv) continues north along the African east-coast as the Agulhas Undercurrent.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Of 89.5 Sv released from the North Atlantic, 3.6 Sv leaves the South Atlantic south of the Agulhas Bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] However, 0.9 Sv recirculate in the basin north of the Walvis Ridge for centuries, of which 50-90% end up flowing south of the Agulhas Bank within 300 years, increasing the net inter-oceanic exchange with 4.1-4.5 Sv.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Alphard Banks are a small group of long extinct volcanic seamounts on the Agulhas Bank south of Cape Agulhas.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] They rise from the bottom at about 80 m to about 14 m on the top.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] They are the southernmost recreational diving sites on the African continental shelf, and are seldom dived due to the distance offshore.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Alpard banks are in the Alphard Banks Controlled-Pelagic Linefish Zone of the Agulhas Bank Complex Marine Protected Area.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The habitats are depth and profile related, with the shallower, flatter, areas of the pinnacle tops dominated by spiny kelp (*Ecklonia radiata*), and encrusting invertebrates, and the deeper, steeper, areas below 30 m having little kelp and a more upright invertebrate community.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Dalgleish Bank is a relatively shallow area of rocky reef about 11 km offshore of Buffelsbaai, or 15.5 km, (about 8.3 nautical miles) bearing 218°T from Knysna Heads.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Maximum depth in the immediate vicinity is about 80 m, and the shallowest part of the reef is about 29 m.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The oldest rock found along the coastline of the Agulhas Bank are eugeosynclinal sediments of the up to 3 km (1.9 mi) thick Kaaimans Group deposited during continental rifting some 900 million years ago (Mya).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The proto-South Atlantic closed during the Saldanian orogeny to form part of the supercontinent Gondwana (700-600 Mya).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Cape granites were emplaced and the Kaaimans Group rocks were folded and thermally metamorphosed during this period.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The formation of the main basin in the Cape Province commenced 570 Mya and lasted for 200 My.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Table Mountain Group is 4 km (2.5 mi) thick and an erosional unconformity marking its base is composed of both terrestrial and marine sediments.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Synclines along the coast of the southern Cape contains sediments from the Bokkveld Group.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Cape Fold Belt (CFB) rocks and the Karoo Basin were deposited 450 Mya; the Cape Supergroup 450-300 Mya during a series of transgression-regression cycles.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Pan-African thrusts were reactivated 270-215 Mya to form the CFB which was then part of a continuous fold belt that developed during the Gondwanide orogeny together with Sierra de la Ventana (Argentina), Pensacola Mountains (East Antarctica), and Ellsworth Mountains (West Antarctica).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] In the late Carboniferous and early Jurassic, the Karoo Supergroup was deposited in the Karoo Basin north of where the CFB is located today, and covering nearly two-thirds of present-day South Africa.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Basaltic lavas were extruded 183 Mya to form the Karoo large igneous province; a volcanism caused by the Bouvet hotspot which is linked to the Gondwana break-up.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Bouvet hotspot was located in or near present-day South Africa from the late Triassic 220 mya and until the Africa-Antarctica breakup 120 mya.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Bouvet hotspot track stretches south-east from the African continent, near the South Africa-Mozambique border, and east of the AFFZ down to Bouvet Island/Bouvet triple junction in the South Atlantic.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] 100 Mya, the region where the triple junction was located passed over the hotspot, resulting in a continuous eruption that lasted to about 94 Mya and the seafloor spreading that still separates Antarctica, Africa, and South America.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Agulhas-Falkland Fracture Zone (AFFZ) stretches 1,200 kilometres (750 mi) across the South Atlantic.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] It is one of the largest and most spectacular fracture zones on Earth.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] It developed during the Early Cretaceous as West Gondwana (South America) broke up from Africa.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The AFFZ is characterized by a pronounced topographic anomaly, the Agulhas Ridge (41°S,16°E-43°S,9°E) which rises more than 2 km above the surrounding sea floor.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The only equivalent in size are the neighbouring Diaz Ridge and the Falkland Escarpment.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Agulhas Ridge is unique because it was not formed during the continental breakup during the Cretaceous and because it separates oceanic crusts of different age, and not oceanic crust (~14 km thick) from continental crust (25 km thick).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The sedimentary fill of these basins developed as the northern edge of the Falkland Plateau separated from the South African southern margin during the early Cretaceous.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Diaz Marginal Ridge (DMR) separates these basins from the AFFZ.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The DMR is buried under 200–250 m (660–820 ft) of sediments and sedimentary rocks and 150–200 m (490–660 ft) of this sedimentary material is undisturbed Cretaceous sediments younger than the oldest Cretaceous sedimentary rocks in the Southern Outeniqua Basin.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The DMR must therefore have formed after the initial West Gondwana breakup 130-90 Mya.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The DMR probably formed when new, hot oceanic crust slid past old, cold continental crust and the contrast in temperatures induced a thermal uplift.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] As West Gondwana drifted away from Africa roughly 125 Myr, the South Atlantic seafloor formed between them and magnetic anomalies north of the AFFZ reflects phase of the seafloor spreading.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] South of the AFFZ traces can be found of how the Falkland Plateau and the Agulhas Bank moved relative to each other.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] On a modern map, the Falkland Plateau can still be rotated and fitted into the Natal Valley in the Indian Ocean east of South Africa.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Alphard Tertiary Igneous Province includes Palaeocene tuffs, trachybasalts, aegirine–augite trachytes and aegirine–augite phonolitic trachytes, which have been radiometrically dated at about 58 million years old.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The intrusions appear to be tectonic effects.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] One of the largest known slumps occurred on the south-eastern edge of the Agulhas Bank in the Pliocene or more recently.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] It is a composite slump with proximal and distal allochthonous sediment masses separated by a large glide plane scar.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] In the western part, the sediments are dammed by basement ridges, but, in the eastern part, they have spread into the Transkei Basin.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] A series of slump scarps along the western edge of the shelf are 18–2 Mya, but covered by younger sediments brought there by the Benguela upwelling.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Anatomically modern humans evolved around 200 kya.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The genetic diversity in the human lineage is relatively low, which indicate one or several population bottlenecks late in our lineage.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] It has been estimated that the population was limited to perhaps 600 individuals during the MIS 6 glacial stage (195-125 kya), one of the longest cold periods in the Quaternary of Africa.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] A technological and behavioural revolution that occurred globally about 50 kya led to a cultural complexity which happened in South Africa around 120-70 kya.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Cape Floral Region is a thin coastal strip and a botanic hotspot which developed at the confluence of the Benguela Upwelling and Agulhas Current.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] According to what professor Curtis Marean calls the "Cape Floral Region – South Coast Model" for the origins of modern humans, the early hunter-gatherers survived on shellfish, as well as geophytes, fur seal, fish, seabirds, and wash-ups found on the exposed Agulhas Bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The bank slopes into the sea and a reconstruction of how the coastline has changed over 440 kya shows that the coast during the Pleistocene was located as far as 90 km (56 mi) from the present coast.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The present South African southern coastal plain (SCP) is still separated from the rest of Africa by the Cape Fold Belt.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] During glacial maxima the sea-level dropped 120 metres (390 ft).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] This not only left large parts of the Agulhas Bank exposed, which greatly expanded the area of the SCP, but it also reconnected the SCP to the rest of Africa by the shallow water shelves, which broke the isolation of the SCP.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Modern humans evolved on the SCP and the fluctuation in sea-levels would have resulted in a significant variation in selective pressure.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] No fossil records are known from the now submerged shelf, but a series of key fossil sites along the coastal margin of the present SCP provide earliest traces of anatomically modern humans and the use of marine resources.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] South Africa began oil exploration on the Agulhas Bank in the 1980s.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Of more than 200 offshore wells in South Africa, most are found on Bredasdorp Basin on the Agulhas Bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Agulhas Bank is also significant for fisheries who use demersal trawling, demersal longline fishing, and midwater trawl fishing on the bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Squid and small pelagic fishes are also caught.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Before the introduction of the EEZ, foreign fisheries used roch-hopper gear trawling on the bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Most of the catches are short-lived shelf-zone pelagic species and more long-lived deep-water species.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The large populations of sardine and anchovy also present on the shelf follow an annual cycle.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Anchovy spawn on the western Agulhas Bank in early summer while the sardines span over a broader season and area — eggs are transported by currents to the nursery area in the St Helena Bay on the South African west coast from where juvenile then migrate back to the Agulhas Bank to spawn.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] South Africa has a relatively large fishing industry mostly catching pelagic pilchard and anchovy and demersal hake on the south and western coasts.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Though the east coast has fewer commercial fisheries, the large human population along there has resulted in overexploitation of coastal fish and invertebrate stocks by recreational and subsistence fishers.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] A small aquaculture industry produces mussels and oysters offshore.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] All these species are relatively common and are considered having an important role in the ecosystem.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] There are at least 12,914 marine species in South Africa, but small bodied species are poorly documented and the abyssal zone is almost completely unexplored.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Almost a quarter of South Africa's coast line is protected, excluding deeper water.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Fisheries are one of the major threats to the biodiversity of the Agulhas Bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Copepods comprise 90% of the zooplankton carbon on the Agulhas Bank, and are thus an important source of food for pelagic fish and juvenile squids.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The population of *Calanus agulhensis*, a large species that dominates the copepod community in terms of biomass, has a center of distribution on the central Agulhas Bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Since 1997 the copepod biomass on the central Agulhas Bank has declined significantly while the biomass of pelagic fish has increased significantly.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] While it is likely that predation has played an important role in the copepod decline, global warming (sea surface temperature and chlorophyll A abundance) is believed to have contributed to a smaller population.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The shelf edge along the bank's southern tip is subject to sporadic upwelling.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] This slope and its surrounding seamounts are the spawning ground for sardine, anchovy, and horse mackerel.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Eddies help transport water inshore and link the spawning habitat with important nursery areas.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Eggs and larvae laid by the anchovy are transported via the Good Hope Jet to Africa's southwestern coast where they mature.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Young anchovies then return to the Agulhas Bank to spawn.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Young sardine and anchovy congregate along the west coast between March and September before they migrate to their spawning grounds on the Agulhas Bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Sardines of intermediate age are present on the western Agulhas Bank between January and April before migrating to KwaZulu-Natal for winter.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The spawning on the Agulhas Bank takes place 30–130 km (19–81 mi) offshore from September to February.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The bank is the spawning area of deep reef fish species, including the threatened endemic red steenbras (*Petrus rupestris*).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Other species have been overexploited, including daggerhead seabream or dageraad (*Chrysoblephus cristiceps*), black musselcracker (*Cymatoceps nasutus*), and silver kob (*Argyrosomus inodorus*).
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] 57 species of sharks have been reported off the western coast of South Africa, of which 21 are squaloid sharks.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The main food source for African penguins (*Spheniscus demersus*) is anchovy and sardine which they forage between Cape Columbine and the central Agulhas Bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The birds have colonies on Dassen Island, on the South African west coast, and Bird Island, on the south coast.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] African penguins breed opportunistically, following the anchovy and sardine: from February to September on the Western Cape but from January to July on St Croix Island off Eastern Cape.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] After breeding, the birds forage further offshore: 10–15 km (6.2–9.3 mi) off the western coast and up to 40 km (25 mi) from their colonies off Eastern Cape.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] In 2005, when Korean and Philippine vessels started longline fishing along the edges of the Agulhas Bank, seabird bycatch became a huge problem.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Large numbers of albatrosses and petrels were killed — in average 0.6 birds per 1000 hooks, but up to 18 birds per 1000 hooks were reported.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Since 2007, however, more restrictive permit conditions for foreign-flagged fleets and the use of birds scaring lines have decreased the number of killed birds by 85%.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Cape fur seals are present along the South African coast.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Fur seals are protected in South Africa since 1893 although a small number are occasionally culled to protect sea birds.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Many seals are caught in fishery nets and boat propellers, but the seals are also regularly accused of stealing fish from the fisheries.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Sharks are known to prey on them, but in 2012 a cape fur seal was observed preying on and consuming a mid-sized blue shark.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] 51 species, or more than 50%, of the recognized species of cetaceans are present in the southern African subregion (between the equator and the Antarctic ice edge), of which 36 have been sighted in South African and Namibian waters.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] A vulnerable population of fish-eating killer whales are present offshore on the Agulhas Bank.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Observations peak in January while few are sighted in April and May.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The killer whales move in pods of 1-4 individuals and are mostly observed over the shelf edge off the south-east coast.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] An analysis of killer whale mtDNA has shown that there was a peak inter-oceanic migration events during the Eemian interglacial period, 131-114 kya.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] This peak coincides with a period of maximal Agulhas leakage which promoted a rapid and episodic interchange of killer whale lineages.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] During this period killer whales and other marine top predators, such as the great white shark, colonised the North Atlantic and Mediterranean by following their prey — bluefin tuna and swordfish.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] A vagrant Commerson's dolphin — a species with two isolated populations, one along the southern coast of Argentina and the other around the Kerguelen Islands — was sighted on the Agulhas Bank in 2004.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] It is not known from which population the sighted individual stems.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] The Kerguelen Islands are located 4,200 km (2,600 mi) and South America 6,300 km (3,900 mi) from the Agulhas Bank, but the west-ward direction of the Antarctic Circumpolar Current would force the dolphin to swim against the current from the Kerguelen Islands.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Fossil beaked whales have been recovered by trawling from the seafloor off South Africa.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] Stranded pygmy sperm whales have been recorded on both the east and west coasts of South Africa.
[src:algaculture/agulhas-bank] There are several marine protected areas on the Agulhas Bank.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Several species of algae are raised for food.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Australian scientists at Flinders University in Adelaide have been experimenting with using marine microalgae to produce proteins for human consumption, creating products like "caviar", vegan burgers, meat substitute, jams and other food spreads.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] By manipulating microalgae in a laboratory, the protein and other nutrient contents could be increased, and flavours changed to make them more palatable.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] These foods leave a much lighter carbon footprint than other forms of protein, as the microalgae absorb rather than produce carbon dioxide, which contributes to the greenhouse gases.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Both microalgae and macroalgae are used to make agar.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] For centuries seaweed has been used as fertilizer.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] It is also an excellent source of potassium for manufacture of potash and potassium nitrate.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Some types of microalgae can be used this way as well.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] With concern over global warming, new methods for the thorough and efficient capture of CO2 are being sought out.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The carbon dioxide that a carbon-fuel burning plant produces can feed into open or closed algae systems, fixing the CO2 and accelerating algae growth.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Untreated sewage can supply additional nutrients, thus turning two pollutants into valuable commodities.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Waste high-purity CO2 as well as sequestered carbon from the atmosphere can be used, with potential significant benefits for climate change mitigation.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Algae cultivation is under study for uranium/plutonium sequestration and purifying fertilizer runoff.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Business, academia and governments are exploring the possibility of using algae to make gasoline, bio-diesel, biogas and other fuels.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Algae itself may be used as a biofuel, and additionally be used to create hydrogen.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Microalgae are also researched for hydrogen production – e.g. micro-droplets for algal cells or synergistic algal-bacterial multicellular spheroid microbial reactors capable of producing oxygen as well as hydrogen via photosynthesis in daylight under air.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The BIQ House built in 2013 in Germany is a showcase experimental bionic house using glass facade panels for the cultivation of micro algae.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Once the panels heat up thermal energy can also be extracted through a heat exchanger in order to supply warm water to the building.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The technology is still in an early stage and not yet fit for a wider use.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The Green Power House in Montana, United States used newly developed Algae Aquaculture Technology within a system that uses sunlight and woody debris waste from a lumber mill for providing nutrients to eight algae ponds of the AACT that cover its floor.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] In 2022, news outlets reported about the development of algae biopanels by a company for sustainable energy generation with unclear viability.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Seaweed grows in shallow and coastal areas, and captures significant amounts of carbon that can be transported to the deep ocean by oceanic mechanisms; seaweed reaching the deep ocean sequester carbon and prevent it from exchanging with the atmosphere over millennia.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Growing seaweed offshore with the purpose of sinking the seaweed in the depths of the sea to sequester carbon has been suggested.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] In addition, seaweed grows very fast and can theoretically be harvested and processed to generate biomethane, via anaerobic digestion to generate electricity, via cogeneration/CHP or as a replacement for natural gas.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Both macroalgae and microalgae are being investigated as possible means of carbon sequestration.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Marine phytoplankton perform half of the global photosynthetic CO2 fixation (net global primary production of ~50 Pg C per year) and half of the oxygen production despite amounting to only ~1% of global plant biomass.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Because algae lack the complex lignin associated with terrestrial plants, the carbon in algae is released into the atmosphere more rapidly than carbon captured on land.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Algae have been proposed as a short-term storage pool of carbon that can be used as a feedstock for the production of various biogenic fuels.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Large-scale seaweed farming could sequester significant amounts of carbon.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Wild seaweed will sequester large amount of carbon through dissolved particles of organic matter being transported to deep ocean seafloors where it will become buried and remain for long periods of time.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] With respect to carbon farming, the potential growth of seaweed for carbon farming would see the harvested seaweed transported to the deep ocean for long-term burial.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Seaweed farming occurs mostly in the Asian Pacific coastal areas where it has been a rapidly increasing market.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" on seaweed farming as a mitigation tactic.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Cultured strains of a common coral microalgal endosymbionts are researched as a potential way to increase corals' thermal tolerance for climate resilience and bleaching tolerance.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Cultured microalgae is used in research and development for potential medical applications, in particular for microbots such as biohybrid microswimmers for targeted drug delivery.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Cultivated algae serve many other purposes, including cosmetics, animal feed, bioplastic production, dyes and colorant production, chemical feedstock production, and pharmaceutical ingredients.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Most growers prefer monocultural production and go to considerable lengths to maintain the purity of their cultures.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] However, the microbiological contaminants are still under investigation.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] With mixed cultures, one species comes to dominate over time and if a non-dominant species is believed to have particular value, it is necessary to obtain pure cultures in order to cultivate this species.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Individual species cultures are also much needed for research purposes.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] A common method of obtaining pure cultures is serial dilution.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Cultivators dilute either a wild sample or a lab sample containing the desired algae with filtered water and introduce small aliquots (measures of this solution) into a large number of small growing containers.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Dilution follows a microscopic examination of the source culture that predicts that a few of the growing containers contain a single cell of the desired species.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Following a suitable period on a light table, cultivators again use the microscope to identify containers to start larger cultures.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Another approach is to use a special medium which excludes other organisms, including invasive algae.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] For example, *Dunaliella* is a commonly grown genus of microalgae which flourishes in extremely salty water that few other organisms can tolerate.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Alternatively, mixed algae cultures can work well for larval mollusks.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] First, the cultivator filters the sea water to remove algae which are too large for the larvae to eat.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Next, the cultivator adds nutrients and possibly aerates the result.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] After one or two days in a greenhouse or outdoors, the resulting thin soup of mixed algae is ready for the larvae.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] An advantage of this method is low maintenance.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Water, carbon dioxide, minerals and light are all important factors in cultivation, and different algae have different requirements.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The basic reaction for algae growth in water is carbon dioxide + light energy + water = glucose + oxygen + water.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] It is also possible to grow certain types of algae without light, these types of algae consume sugars (such as glucose).
[src:algaculture/algaculture] This is known as *heterotrophic* growth.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The water must be in a temperature range that will support the specific algal species being grown mostly between 15˚C and 35˚C.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] In a typical algal-cultivation system, such as an open pond, light only penetrates the top 3 to 4 inches (76–102 mm) of the water, though this depends on the algae density.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] As the algae grow and multiply, the culture becomes so dense that it blocks light from reaching deeper into the water.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] To use deeper ponds, growers agitate the water, circulating the algae so that it does not remain on the surface.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Paddle wheels can stir the water and compressed air coming from the bottom lifts algae from the lower regions.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Agitation also helps prevent over-exposure to the sun.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Another means of supplying light is to place the light *in* the system.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Glow plates made from sheets of plastic or glass and placed within the tank offer precise control over light intensity, and distribute it more evenly.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] They are seldom used, however, due to high cost.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The odor associated with bogs, swamps, and other stagnant waters can be due to oxygen depletion caused by the decay of deceased algal blooms.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Under anoxic conditions, the bacteria inhabiting algae cultures break down the organic material and produce hydrogen sulfide and ammonia, which causes the odor.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] This hypoxia often results in the death of aquatic animals.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] In a system where algae is intentionally cultivated, maintained, and harvested, neither eutrophication nor hypoxia are likely to occur.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Some living algae and bacteria also produce odorous chemicals, particularly certain cyanobacteria (previously classed as blue-green algae) such as *Anabaena*.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The most well known of these odor-causing chemicals are MIB (2-methylisoborneol) and geosmin.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] They give a musty or earthy odor that can be quite strong.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Eventual death of the cyanobacteria releases additional gas that is trapped in the cells.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] These chemicals are detectable at very low levels – in the parts per billion range – and are responsible for many "taste and odor" issues in drinking water treatment and distribution.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Cyanobacteria can also produce chemical toxins that have been a problem in drinking water.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Nutrients such as nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K) serve as fertilizer for algae, and are generally necessary for growth.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Silica and iron, as well as several trace elements, may also be considered important marine nutrients as the lack of one can limit the growth of, or productivity in, a given area.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Carbon dioxide is also essential; usually an input of CO2 is required for fast-paced algal growth.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] These elements must be dissolved into the water, in bio-available forms, for algae to grow.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] An open system of algae cultivation involves the growth of algae in shallow water streams which could originate from a natural system or artificially prepared.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] In this system, algae can be cultivated in natural water bodies like lakes, rivers, and in oceans, as well as artificial ponds made up of concrete, plastic, pond liners or variety of materials.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The open system of algae cultivation is simple and cost-effective, making it an attractive option for commercial production of algae-based products.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Open ponds are highly vulnerable to contamination by other microorganisms, such as other algal species or bacteria.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Thus cultivators usually choose closed systems for monocultures.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Open systems also do not offer control over temperature and lighting.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The growing season is largely dependent on location and, aside from tropical areas, is limited to the warmer months.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Open pond systems are cheaper to construct, at the minimum requiring only a trench or pond.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Large ponds have the largest production capacities relative to other systems of comparable cost.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Also, open pond cultivation can exploit unusual conditions that suit only specific algae.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] For instance, *Dunaliella salina* grow in extremely salty water; these unusual media exclude other types of organisms, allowing the growth of pure cultures in open ponds.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Open culture can also work if there is a system of harvesting only the desired algae, or if the ponds are frequently re-inoculated before invasive organisms can multiply significantly.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The latter approach is frequently employed by Chlorella farmers, as the growth conditions for Chlorella do not exclude competing algae.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The former approach can be employed in the case of some chain diatoms since they can be filtered from a stream of water flowing through an outflow pipe.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] A "pillow case" of a fine mesh cloth is tied over the outflow pipe allowing other algae to escape.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The chain diatoms are held in the bag and feed shrimp larvae (in Eastern hatcheries) and inoculate new tanks or ponds.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Enclosing a pond with a transparent or translucent barrier effectively turns it into a greenhouse.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] This solves many of the problems associated with an open system.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] It allows more species to be grown, it allows the species that are being grown to stay dominant, and it extends the growing season – if heated, the pond can produce year round.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Open race way ponds were used for removal of lead using live *Spirulina (Arthospira) sp*.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] A lagoon is a type of aquatic ecosystem that is characterized by a shallow body of water that is separated from the open ocean by natural barriers such as sandbars, barrier islands, or coral reefs.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The Australian company Cognis Australia is a well-known company that specializes in producing β-carotene from *Dunaliella salina* harvested from hypersaline extensive ponds located in Hutt Lagoon and Whyalla.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] These ponds are primarily used for wastewater treatment, and the production of *D. salina* is a secondary benefit.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Open sea cultivation is a method of cultivating seaweed in the open ocean, as well as on a costal line in shallow water.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Seaweed farming industry serves commercial needs for various products such as food, feed, pharma chemicals, cosmetics, biofuels, and bio-stimulants.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Seaweed extracts act as bio-stimulants, reducing biotic stress and increasing crop production.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Additionally, it presents opportunities for creating animal and human nutrition products that can improve immunity and productivity.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Open ocean seaweed cultivation is an eco-friendly technology that doesn't require land, fresh water, or chemicals.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] It also helps mitigate the effects of climate change by sequestering CO2.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Open sea cultivation method involves the use of rafts or ropes anchored in the ocean, where the seaweed grows attached to them.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] This method is widely used for commercial seaweed farming, as it allows for large-scale production and harvesting.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The process of open sea cultivation of seaweed involves several steps.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] First, a suitable site in the ocean is identified, based on factors such as water depth, temperature, salinity, and nutrient availability.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Once a site is chosen, ropes or rafts are anchored in the water, and the seed pieces of seaweed are attached to them using specialized equipment.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The seaweed is then left to grow for several months, during which it absorbs nutrients from the water and sunlight through photosynthesis.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Raceway-type ponds and lakes are open to the elements.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] They are one of the most common and economic methods of large-scale algae cultivation, and offer several advantages over other cultivation methods.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] An open raceway pond is a shallow, rectangular-shaped pond used for the cultivation of algae.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Because it is designed to circulate water in a continuous loop or raceway, allowing algae to grow in a controlled environment.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Open system is a low-cost method of algae cultivation, and it is relatively easy to construct and maintain.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The pond is typically lined with a synthetic material, such as polyethylene (HDPE) or polyvinyl chloride, to prevent the loss of water and nutrients.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The pond is also equipped with paddlewheels or other types of mechanical devices to provide mixing and aeration.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] High-Rate Algal Ponds (HRAPs) are a type of open algae cultivation system that has gained popularity in recent years due to their efficiency and low cost of operation.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] HRAPs are shallow ponds, typically between 0.1 and 0.4 meters deep, that are used for the cultivation of algae.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The ponds are equipped with a paddlewheel or other type of mechanical agitation system that provides mixing and aeration, which promotes algae growth.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] HRAP system is also recommended in wastewater treatment using algae.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Algae can also be grown in a photobioreactor (PBR).
[src:algaculture/algaculture] A PBR is a bioreactor which incorporates a light source.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Virtually any translucent container could be called a PBR; however, the term is more commonly used to define a closed system, as opposed to an open tank or pond.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Because PBR systems are closed, the cultivator must provide all nutrients, including CO 2.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] A PBR can operate in "batch mode", which involves restocking the reactor after each harvest, but it is also possible to grow and harvest continuously.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Continuous operation requires precise control of all elements to prevent immediate collapse.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The grower provides sterilized water, nutrients, air, and carbon dioxide at the correct rates.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] This allows the reactor to operate for long periods.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] An advantage is that algae that grows in the "log phase" is generally of higher nutrient content than old "senescent" algae.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Algal culture is the culturing of algae in ponds or other resources.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Maximum productivity occurs when the "exchange rate" (time to exchange one volume of liquid) is equal to the "doubling time" (in mass or volume) of the algae.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] PBRs can hold the culture in suspension, or they can provide a substrate on which the culture can form a biofilm.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Biofilm-based PBRs have the advantage that they can produce far higher yields for a given water volume, but they can suffer from problems with cells separating from the substrate due to the water flow required to transport gases and nutrients to the culture.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Flat panel PBRs consist of a series of flat, transparent panels that are stacked on top of each other, creating a thin layer of liquid between them.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Algae are grown in this thin layer of liquid, which is continuously circulated to promote mixing and prevent stagnation.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The panels are typically made of glass or plastic and can be arranged in various configurations to optimize light exposure.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Flat panel PBRs are generally used for low-to-medium density cultivation and are well-suited for species that require lower light intensity and maximum surface area for optimum light exposure.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] The temperature control in Flat panel PBR system is carried out by cooling down the culture in reservoir chamber using chilled water jacket as well as by sprinkling cold water on the flat panel surface.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Tubular PBRs consist of long, transparent tubes that are either vertically or horizontally oriented.
[src:algaculture/algaculture] Algae are grown inside the tubes, which are typically made of glass or plastic.
